   126	
   127	1.  Introduction
   128	
   129	1.1  Purpose of this Work
   130	
   131	   This handbook is a guide to setting computer security policies and
   132	   procedures for sites that have systems on the Internet.  This guide
   133	   lists issues and factors that a site must consider when setting their
   134	   own policies.  It makes some recommendations and gives discussions of
   135	   relevant areas.
   136	
   137	   This guide is only a framework for setting security policies and
   138	   procedures.  In order to have an effective set of policies and
   139	   procedures, a site will have to make many decisions, gain agreement,
   140	   and then communicate and implement the policies.
   141	
   142	1.2  Audience
   143	
   144	   The audience for this work are system administrators and decision
   145	   makers (who are more traditionally called "administrators" or "middle
   146	   management") at sites.  This document is not directed at programmers
   147	   or those trying to create secure programs or systems.  The focus of
   148	   this document is on the policies and procedures that need to be in
   149	   place to support any technical security features that a site may be
   150	   implementing.
   151	
   152	   The primary audience for this work are sites that are members of the
   153	   Internet community.  However, this document should be useful to any
   154	   site that allows communication with other sites.  As a general guide
   155	   to security policies, this document may also be useful to sites with
   156	   isolated systems.
   157	
   158	
   159	
   160	
   161	
   162	
   163	
   164	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                     [Page 3]
   165	
   166	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
   167	
   168	
   169	1.3  Definitions
   170	
   171	   For the purposes of this guide, a "site" is any organization that
   172	   owns computers or network-related resources.  These resources may
   173	   include host computers that users use, routers, terminal servers,
   174	   PC's or other devices that have access to the Internet.  A site may
   175	   be a end user of Internet services or a service provider such as a
   176	   regional network.  However, most of the focus of this guide is on
   177	   those end users of Internet services.
   178	
   179	   We assume that the site has the ability to set policies and
   180	   procedures for itself with the concurrence and support from those who
   181	   actually own the resources.
   182	
   183	   The "Internet" is those set of networks and machines that use the
   184	   TCP/IP protocol suite, connected through gateways, and sharing a
   185	   common name and address spaces [1].
   186	
   187	   The term "system administrator" is used to cover all those who are
   188	   responsible for the day-to-day operation of resources.  This may be a
   189	   number of individuals or an organization.
   190	
   191	   The term "decision maker" refers to those people at a site who set or
   192	   approve policy.  These are often (but not always) the people who own
   193	   the resources.
   194	
   195	1.4  Related Work
   196	
   197	   The IETF Security Policy Working Group (SPWG) is working on a set of
   198	   recommended security policy guidelines for the Internet [23].  These
   199	   guidelines may be adopted as policy by regional networks or owners of
   200	   other resources.  This handbook should be a useful tool to help sites
   201	   implement those policies as desired or required.  However, even
   202	   implementing the proposed policies isn't enough to secure a site.
   203	   The proposed Internet policies deal only with network access
   204	   security.  It says nothing about how sites should deal with local
   205	   security issues.
   206	
   207	1.5  Scope
   208	
   209	   This document covers issues about what a computer security policy
   210	   should contain, what kinds of procedures are need to enforce
   211	   security, and some recommendations about how to deal with the
   212	   problem.  When developing a security policy, close attention should
   213	   be made not only on the security needs and requirements of the local
   214	   network, but also the security needs and requirements of the other
   215	   interconnected networks.
   216	
   217	
   218	
   219	
   220	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                     [Page 4]
   221	
   222	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
   223	
   224	
   225	   This is not a cookbook for computer security.  Each site has
   226	   different needs; the security needs of a corporation might well be
   227	   different than the security needs of an academic institution.  Any
   228	   security plan has to conform to the needs and culture of the site.
   229	
   230	   This handbook does not cover details of how to do risk assessment,
   231	   contingency planning, or physical security.  These things are
   232	   essential in setting and implementing effective security policy, but
   233	   this document leaves treatment of those issues to other documents.
   234	   We will try to provide some pointers in that direction.
   235	
   236	   This document also doesn't talk about how to design or implement
   237	   secure systems or programs.
   238	
   239	1.6  Why Do We Need Security Policies and Procedures?
   240	
   241	   For most sites, the interest in computer security is proportional to
   242	   the perception of risk and threats.
   243	
   244	   The world of computers has changed dramatically over the past
   245	   twenty-five years.  Twenty-five years ago, most computers were
   246	   centralized and managed by data centers.  Computers were kept in
   247	   locked rooms and staffs of people made sure they were carefully
   248	   managed and physically secured.  Links outside a site were unusual.
   249	   Computer security threats were rare, and were basically concerned
   250	   with insiders: authorized users misusing accounts, theft and
   251	   vandalism, and so forth.  These threats were well understood and
   252	   dealt with using standard techniques: computers behind locked doors,
   253	   and accounting for all resources.
   254	
   255	   Computing in the 1990's is radically different.  Many systems are in
   256	   private offices and labs, often managed by individuals or persons
   257	   employed outside a computer center.  Many systems are connected into
   258	   the Internet, and from there around the world: the United States,
   259	   Europe, Asia, and Australia are all connected together.
   260	
   261	   Security threats are different today.  The time honored advice says
   262	   "don't write your password down and put it in your desk" lest someone
   263	   find it.  With world-wide Internet connections, someone could get
   264	   into your system from the other side of the world and steal your
   265	   password in the middle of the night when your building is locked up.
   266	   Viruses and worms can be passed from machine to machine.  The
   267	   Internet allows the electronic equivalent of the thief who looks for
   268	   open windows and doors; now a person can check hundreds of machines
   269	   for vulnerabilities in a few hours.
   270	
   271	   System administrators and decision makers have to understand the
   272	   security threats that exist, what the risk and cost of a problem
   273	
   274	
   275	
   276	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                     [Page 5]
   277	
   278	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
   279	
   280	
   281	   would be, and what kind of action they want to take (if any) to
   282	   prevent and respond to security threats.
   283	
   284	   As an illustration of some of the issues that need to be dealt with
   285	   in security problems, consider the following scenarios (thanks to
   286	   Russell Brand [2, BRAND] for these):
   287	
   288	      - A system programmer gets a call reporting that a
   289	        major underground cracker newsletter is being
   290	        distributed from the administrative machine at his
   291	        center to five thousand sites in the US and
   292	        Western Europe.
   293	
   294	        Eight weeks later, the authorities call to inform
   295	        you the information in one of these newsletters
   296	        was used to disable "911" in a major city for
   297	        five hours.
   298	
   299	      - A user calls in to report that he can't login to his
   300	        account at 3 o'clock in the morning on a Saturday.  The
   301	        system staffer can't login either.  After rebooting to
   302	        single user mode, he finds that password file is empty.
   303	        By Monday morning, your staff determines that a number
   304	        of privileged file transfers took place between this
   305	        machine and a local university.
   306	
   307	        Tuesday morning a copy of the deleted password file is
   308	        found on the university machine along with password
   309	        files for a dozen other machines.
   310	
   311	        A week later you find that your system initialization
   312	        files had been altered in a hostile fashion.
   313	
   314	      - You receive a call saying that a breakin to a government
   315	        lab occurred from one of your center's machines.  You
   316	        are requested to provide accounting files to help
   317	        trackdown the attacker.
   318	
   319	        A week later you are given a list of machines at your
   320	        site that have been broken into.
   321	
   322	       - A reporter calls up asking about the breakin at your
   323	         center.  You haven't heard of any such breakin.
   324	
   325	        Three days later, you learn that there was a breakin.
   326	        The center director had his wife's name as a password.
   327	
   328	
   329	
   330	
   331	
   332	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                     [Page 6]
   333	
   334	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
   335	
   336	
   337	      - A change in system binaries is detected.
   338	
   339	        The day that it is corrected, they again are changed.
   340	        This repeats itself for some weeks.
   341	
   342	      - If an intruder is found on your system, should you
   343	        leave the system open to monitor the situation or should
   344	        you close down the holes and open them up again later?
   345	
   346	      - If an intruder is using your site, should you call law
   347	        enforcement?  Who makes that decision?  If law enforcement asks
   348	        you to leave your site open, who makes that decision?
   349	
   350	      - What steps should be taken if another site calls you and says
   351	        they see activity coming from an account on your system?  What
   352	        if the account is owned by a local manager?
   353	
   354	1.7  Basic Approach
   355	
   356	   Setting security policies and procedures really means developing a
   357	   plan for how to deal with computer security.  One way to approach
   358	   this task is suggested by Fites, et. al. [3, FITES]:
   359	
   360	      -  Look at what you are trying to protect.
   361	      -  Look at what you need to protect it from.
   362	      -  Determine how likely the threats are.
   363	      -  Implement measures which will protect your assets in a
   364	         cost-effective manner.
   365	      -  Review the process continuously, and improve things every time
   366	         a weakness is found.
   367	
   368	   This handbook will concentrate mostly on the last two steps, but the
   369	   first three are critically important to making effective decisions
   370	   about security.  One old truism in security is that the cost of
   371	   protecting yourself against a threat should be less than the cost
   372	   recovering if the threat were to strike you.  Without reasonable
   373	   knowledge of what you are protecting and what the likely threats are,
   374	   following this rule could be difficult.
   375	
   376	1.8  Organization of this Document
   377	
   378	   This document is organized into seven parts in addition to this
   379	   introduction.
   380	
   381	   The basic form of each section is to discuss issues that a site might
   382	   want to consider in creating a computer security policy and setting
   383	   procedures to implement that policy.  In some cases, possible options
   384	   are discussed along with the some of the ramifications of those
   385	
   386	
   387	
   388	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                     [Page 7]
   389	
   390	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
   391	
   392	
   393	   choices.  As far as possible, this document tries not to dictate the
   394	   choices a site should make, since these depend on local
   395	   circumstances.  Some of the issues brought up may not apply to all
   396	   sites.  Nonetheless, all sites should at least consider the issues
   397	   brought up here to ensure that they do not miss some important area.
   398	
   399	   The overall flow of the document is to discuss policy issues followed
   400	   by the issues that come up in creating procedures to implement the
   401	   policies.
   402	
   403	   Section 2 discusses setting official site policies for access to
   404	   computing resources.  It also goes into the issue of what happens
   405	   when the policy is violated.  The policies will drive the procedures
   406	   that need to be created, so decision makers will need to make choices
   407	   about policies before many of the procedural issues in following
   408	   sections can be dealt with.  A key part of creating policies is doing
   409	   some kind of risk assessment to decide what really needs to be
   410	   protected and the level of resources that should be applied to
   411	   protect them.
   412	
   413	   Once policies are in place, procedures to prevent future security
   414	   problems should be established.  Section 3 defines and suggests
   415	   actions to take when unauthorized activity is suspected.  Resources
   416	   to prevent secruity breaches are also discussed.
   417	
   418	   Section 4 discusses types of procedures to prevent security problems.
   419	   Prevention is a key to security; as an example, the Computer
   420	   Emergency Response Team/Coordination Center (CERT/CC) at Carnegie-
   421	   Mellon University (CMU) estimates that 80% or more of the problems
   422	   they see have to do with poorly chosen passwords.
   423	
   424	   Section 5 discusses incident handling: what kinds of issues does a
   425	   site face when someone violates the security policy.  Many decisions
   426	   will have to made on the spot as the incident occurs, but many of the
   427	   options and issues can be discussed in advance.  At very least,
   428	   responsibilities and methods of communication can be established
   429	   before an incident.  Again, the choices here are influenced by the
   430	   policies discussed in section 2.
   431	
   432	   Section 6 deals with what happens after a security violation has been
   433	   dealt with.  Security planning is an on-going cycle; just after an
   434	   incident has occurred is an excellent opportunity to improve policies
   435	   and procedures.
   436	
   437	   The rest of the document provides references and an annotated
   438	   bibliography.
   439	
   440	
   441	
   442	
   443	
   444	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                     [Page 8]
   445	
   446	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
   447	
   448	
   449	2.  Establishing Official Site Policy on Computer Security
   450	
   451	2.1  Brief Overview
   452	
   453	   2.1.1  Organization Issues
   454	
   455	      The goal in developing an official site policy on computer
   456	      security is to define the organization's expectations of proper
   457	      computer and network use and to define procedures to prevent and
   458	      respond to security incidents.  In order to do this, aspects of
   459	      the particular organization must be considered.
   460	
   461	      First, the goals and direction of the organization should be
   462	      considered.  For example, a military base may have very different
   463	      security concerns from a those of a university.
   464	
   465	      Second, the site security policy developed must conform to
   466	      existing policies, rules, regulations and laws that the
   467	      organization is subject to.  Therefore it will be necessary to
   468	      identify these and take them into consideration while developing
   469	      the policy.
   470	
   471	      Third, unless the local network is completely isolated and
   472	      standalone, it is necessary to consider security implications in a
   473	      more global context.  The policy should address the issues when
   474	      local security problems develop as a result of a remote site as
   475	      well as when problems occur on remote systems as a result of a
   476	      local host or user.
   477	
   478	   2.1.2  Who Makes the Policy?
   479	
   480	      Policy creation must be a joint effort by technical personnel, who
   481	      understand the full ramifications of the proposed policy and the
   482	      implementation of the policy, and by decision makers who have the
   483	      power to enforce the policy.  A policy which is neither
   484	      implementable nor enforceable is useless.
   485	
   486	      Since a computer security policy can affect everyone in an
   487	      organization, it is worth taking some care to make sure you have
   488	      the right level of authority in on the policy decisions.  Though a
   489	      particular group (such as a campus information services group) may
   490	      have responsibility for enforcing a policy, an even higher group
   491	      may have to support and approve the policy.
   492	
   493	   2.1.3  Who is Involved?
   494	
   495	      Establishing a site policy has the potential for involving every
   496	      computer user at the site in a variety of ways.  Computer users
   497	
   498	
   499	
   500	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                     [Page 9]
   501	
   502	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
   503	
   504	
   505	      may be responsible for personal password administration.  Systems
   506	      managers are obligated to fix security holes and to oversee the
   507	      system.
   508	
   509	      It is critical to get the right set of people involved at the
   510	      start of the process.  There may already be groups concerned with
   511	      security who would consider a computer security policy to be their
   512	      area.  Some of the types of groups that might be involved include
   513	      auditing/control, organizations that deal with physical security,
   514	      campus information systems groups, and so forth.  Asking these
   515	      types of groups to "buy in" from the start can help facilitate the
   516	      acceptance of the policy.
   517	
   518	   2.1.4  Responsibilities
   519	
   520	      A key element of a computer security policy is making sure
   521	      everyone knows their own responsibility for maintaining security.
   522	      A computer security policy cannot anticipate all possibilities;
   523	      however, it can ensure that each kind of problem does have someone
   524	      assigned to deal with it.
   525	
   526	      There may be levels of responsibility associated with a policy on
   527	      computer security.  At one level, each user of a computing
   528	      resource may have a responsibility to protect his account.  A user
   529	      who allows his account to be compromised increases the chances of
   530	      compromising other accounts or resources.
   531	
   532	      System managers may form another responsibility level: they must
   533	      help to ensure the security of the computer system.  Network
   534	      managers may reside at yet another level.
   535	
   536	2.2  Risk Assessment
   537	
   538	   2.2.1  General Discussion
   539	
   540	      One of the most important reasons for creating a computer security
   541	      policy is to ensure that efforts spent on security yield cost
   542	      effective benefits.  Although this may seem obvious, it is
   543	      possible to be mislead about where the effort is needed.  As an
   544	      example, there is a great deal of publicity about intruders on
   545	      computers systems; yet most surveys of computer security show that
   546	      for most organizations, the actual loss from "insiders" is much
   547	      greater.
   548	
   549	      Risk analysis involves determining what you need to protect, what
   550	      you need to protect it from, and how to protect it.  Is is the
   551	      process of examining all of your risks, and ranking those risks by
   552	      level of severity.  This process involves making cost-effective
   553	
   554	
   555	
   556	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 10]
   557	
   558	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
   559	
   560	
   561	      decisions on what you want to protect.  The old security adage
   562	      says that you should not spend more to protect something than it
   563	      is actually worth.
   564	
   565	      A full treatment of risk analysis is outside the scope of this
   566	      document.  [3, FITES] and [16, PFLEEGER] provide introductions to
   567	      this topic.  However, there are two elements of a risk analysis
   568	      that will be briefly covered in the next two sections:
   569	
   570	         1. Identifying the assets
   571	         2. Identifying the threats
   572	
   573	      For each asset, the basic goals of security are availability,
   574	      confidentiality, and integrity.  Each threat should be examined
   575	      with an eye to how the threat could affect these areas.
   576	
   577	   2.2.2  Identifying the Assets
   578	
   579	      One step in a risk analysis is to identify all the things that
   580	      need to be protected.  Some things are obvious, like all the
   581	      various pieces of hardware, but some are overlooked, such as the
   582	      people who actually use the systems. The essential point is to
   583	      list all things that could be affected by a security problem.
   584	
   585	      One list of categories is suggested by Pfleeger [16, PFLEEGER,
   586	      page 459]; this list is adapted from that source:
   587	
   588	         1. Hardware: cpus, boards, keyboards, terminals,
   589	            workstations, personal computers, printers, disk
   590	            drives, communication lines, terminal servers, routers.
   591	
   592	         2. Software: source programs, object programs,
   593	            utilities, diagnostic programs, operating systems,
   594	            communication programs.
   595	
   596	         3. Data: during execution, stored on-line, archived off-line,
   597	            backups, audit logs, databases, in transit over
   598	            communication media.
   599	
   600	         4. People: users, people needed to run systems.
   601	
   602	         5. Documentation: on programs, hardware, systems, local
   603	            administrative procedures.
   604	
   605	         6. Supplies: paper, forms, ribbons, magnetic media.
   606	
   607	
   608	
   609	
   610	
   611	
   612	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 11]
   613	
   614	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
   615	
   616	
   617	   2.2.3  Identifying the Threats
   618	
   619	      Once the assets requiring protection are identified, it is
   620	      necessary to identify threats to those assests.  The threats can
   621	      then be examined to determine what potential for loss exists.  It
   622	      helps to consider from what threats you are trying to protect your
   623	      assets.
   624	
   625	      The following sections describe a few of the possible threats.
   626	
   627	      2.2.3.1  Unauthorized Access
   628	
   629	         A common threat that concerns many sites is unauthorized access
   630	         to computing facilities.  Unauthorized access takes many forms.
   631	         One means of unauthorized access is the use of another user's
   632	         account to gain access to a system.  The use of any computer
   633	         resource without prior permission may be considered
   634	         unauthorized access to computing facilities.
   635	
   636	         The seriousness of an unauthorized access will vary from site
   637	         to site.  For some sites, the mere act of granting access to an
   638	         unauthorized user may cause irreparable harm by negative media
   639	         coverage.  For other sites, an unauthorized access opens the
   640	         door to other security threats.  In addition, some sites may be
   641	         more frequent targets than others; hence the risk from
   642	         unauthorized access will vary from site to site.  The Computer
   643	         Emergency Response Team (CERT - see section 3.9.7.3.1) has
   644	         observed that well-known universities, government sites, and
   645	         military sites seem to attract more intruders.
   646	
   647	      2.2.3.2  Disclosure of Information
   648	
   649	         Another common threat is disclosure of information.  Determine
   650	         the value or sensitivity of the information stored on your
   651	         computers.  Disclosure of a password file might allow for
   652	         future unauthorized accesses.  A glimpse of a proposal may give
   653	         a competitor an unfair advantage.  A technical paper may
   654	         contain years of valuable research.
   655	
   656	      2.2.3.3  Denial of Service
   657	
   658	         Computers and networks provide valuable services to their
   659	         users.  Many people rely on these services in order to perform
   660	         their jobs efficiently.  When these services are not available
   661	         when called upon, a loss in productivity results.
   662	
   663	         Denial of service comes in many forms and might affect users in
   664	         a number of ways.  A network may be rendered unusable by a
   665	
   666	
   667	
   668	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 12]
   669	
   670	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
   671	
   672	
   673	         rogue packet, jamming, or by a disabled network component.  A
   674	         virus might slow down or cripple a computer system.  Each site
   675	         should determine which services are essential, and for each of
   676	         these services determine the affect to the site if that service
   677	         were to become disabled.
   678	
   679	2.3  Policy Issues
   680	
   681	   There are a number of issues that must be addressed when developing a
   682	   security policy.  These are:
   683	
   684	      1.  Who is allowed to use the resources?
   685	      2.  What is the proper use of the resources?
   686	      3.  Who is authorized to grant access and approve usage?
   687	      4.  Who may have system administration privileges?
   688	      5.  What are the user's rights and responsibilities?
   689	      6.  What are the rights and responsibilities of the
   690	          system administrator vs. those of the user?
   691	      7.  What do you do with sensitive information?
   692	
   693	   These issues will be discussed below.  In addition you may wish to
   694	   include a section in your policy concerning ethical use of computing
   695	   resources.  Parker, Swope and Baker [17, PARKER90] and Forester and
   696	   Morrison [18, FORESTER] are two useful references that address
   697	   ethical issues.
   698	
   699	   2.3.1  Who is Allowed to use the Resources?
   700	
   701	      One step you must take in developing your security policy is
   702	      defining who is allowed to use your system and services.  The
   703	      policy should explicitly state who is authorized to use what
   704	      resources.
   705	
   706	   2.3.2  What is the Proper Use of the Resources?
   707	
   708	      After determining who is allowed access to system resources it is
   709	      necessary to provide guidelines for the acceptable use of the
   710	      resources.  You may have different guidelines for different types
   711	      of users (i.e., students, faculty, external users).  The policy
   712	      should state what is acceptable use as well as unacceptable use.
   713	      It should also include types of use that may be restricted.
   714	
   715	      Define limits to access and authority.  You will need to consider
   716	      the level of access various users will have and what resources
   717	      will be available or restricted to various groups of people.
   718	
   719	      Your acceptable use policy should clearly state that individual
   720	      users are responsible for their actions.  Their responsibility
   721	
   722	
   723	
   724	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 13]
   725	
   726	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
   727	
   728	
   729	      exists regardless of the security mechanisms that are in place.
   730	      It should be clearly stated that breaking into accounts or
   731	      bypassing security is not permitted.
   732	
   733	      The following points should be covered when developing an
   734	      acceptable use policy:
   735	
   736	         o Is breaking into accounts permitted?
   737	         o Is cracking passwords permitted?
   738	         o Is disrupting service permitted?
   739	         o Should users assume that a file being world-readable
   740	           grants them the authorization to read it?
   741	         o Should users be permitted to modify files that are
   742	           not their own even if they happen to have write
   743	           permission?
   744	         o Should users share accounts?
   745	
   746	      The answer to most of these questions will be "no".
   747	
   748	      You may wish to incorporate a statement in your policies
   749	      concerning copyrighted and licensed software.  Licensing
   750	      agreements with vendors may require some sort of effort on your
   751	      part to ensure that the license is not violated.  In addition, you
   752	      may wish to inform users that the copying of copyrighted software
   753	      may be a violation of the copyright laws, and is not permitted.
   754	
   755	      Specifically concerning copyrighted and/or licensed software, you
   756	      may wish to include the following information:
   757	
   758	         o Copyrighted and licensed software may not be duplicated
   759	           unless it is explicitly stated that you may do so.
   760	         o Methods of conveying information on the
   761	           copyright/licensed status of software.
   762	         o When in doubt, DON'T COPY.
   763	
   764	      Your acceptable use policy is very important.  A policy which does
   765	      not clearly state what is not permitted may leave you unable to
   766	      prove that a user violated policy.
   767	
   768	      There are exception cases like tiger teams and users or
   769	      administrators wishing for "licenses to hack" -- you may face the
   770	      situation where users will want to "hack" on your services for
   771	      security research purposes.  You should develop a policy that will
   772	      determine whether you will permit this type of research on your
   773	      services and if so, what your guidelines for such research will
   774	      be.
   775	
   776	      Points you may wish to cover in this area:
   777	
   778	
   779	
   780	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 14]
   781	
   782	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
   783	
   784	
   785	         o Whether it is permitted at all.
   786	         o What type of activity is permitted: breaking in, releasing
   787	           worms, releasing viruses, etc..
   788	         o What type of controls must be in place to ensure that it
   789	           does not get out of control (e.g., separate a segment of
   790	           your network for these tests).
   791	         o How you will protect other users from being victims of
   792	           these activities, including external users and networks.
   793	         o The process for obtaining permission to conduct these
   794	           tests.
   795	
   796	      In cases where you do permit these activities, you should isolate
   797	      the portions of the network that are being tested from your main
   798	      network.  Worms and viruses should never be released on a live
   799	      network.
   800	
   801	      You may also wish to employ, contract, or otherwise solicit one or
   802	      more people or organizations to evaluate the security of your
   803	      services, of which may include "hacking".  You may wish to provide
   804	      for this in your policy.
   805	
   806	   2.3.3  Who Is Authorized to Grant Access and Approve Usage?
   807	
   808	      Your policy should state who is authorized to grant access to your
   809	      services.  Further, it must be determined what type of access they
   810	      are permitted to give.  If you do not have control over who is
   811	      granted access to your system, you will not have control over who
   812	      is using your system.  Controlling who has the authorization to
   813	      grant access will also enable you to know who was or was not
   814	      granting access if problems develop later.
   815	
   816	      There are many schemes that can be developed to control the
   817	      distribution of access to your services.  The following are the
   818	      factors that you must consider when determining who will
   819	      distribute access to your services:
   820	
   821	         o Will you be distributing access from a centralized
   822	           point or at various points?
   823	
   824	      You can have a centralized distribution point to a distributed
   825	      system where various sites or departments independently authorize
   826	      access.  The trade off is between security and convenience.  The
   827	      more centralized, the easier to secure.
   828	
   829	         o What methods will you use for creating accounts and
   830	           terminating access?
   831	
   832	      From a security standpoint, you need to examine the mechanism that
   833	
   834	
   835	
   836	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 15]
   837	
   838	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
   839	
   840	
   841	      you will be using to create accounts.  In the least restrictive
   842	      case, the people who are authorized to grant access would be able
   843	      to go into the system directly and create an account by hand or
   844	      through vendor supplied mechanisms.  Generally, these mechanisms
   845	      place a great deal of trust in the person running them, and the
   846	      person running them usually has a large amount of privileges.  If
   847	      this is the choice you make, you need to select someone who is
   848	      trustworthy to perform this task.  The opposite solution is to
   849	      have an integrated system that the people authorized to create
   850	      accounts run, or the users themselves may actually run.  Be aware
   851	      that even in the restrictive case of having a mechanized facility
   852	      to create accounts does not remove the potential for abuse.
   853	
   854	      You should have specific procedures developed for the creation of
   855	      accounts.  These procedures should be well documented to prevent
   856	      confusion and reduce mistakes.  A security vulnerability in the
   857	      account authorization process is not only possible through abuse,
   858	      but is also possible if a mistake is made.  Having clear and well
   859	      documented procedure will help ensure that these mistakes won't
   860	      happen.  You should also be sure that the people who will be
   861	      following these procedures understand them.
   862	
   863	      The granting of access to users is one of the most vulnerable of
   864	      times.  You should ensure that the selection of an initial
   865	      password cannot be easily guessed.  You should avoid using an
   866	      initial password that is a function of the username, is part of
   867	      the user's name, or some algorithmically generated password that
   868	      can easily be guessed.  In addition, you should not permit users
   869	      to continue to use the initial password indefinitely.  If
   870	      possible, you should force users to change the initial password
   871	      the first time they login.  Consider that some users may never
   872	      even login, leaving their password vulnerable indefinitely.  Some
   873	      sites choose to disable accounts that have never been accessed,
   874	      and force the owner to reauthorize opening the account.
   875	
   876	   2.3.4  Who May Have System Administration Privileges?
   877	
   878	      One security decision that needs to be made very carefully is who
   879	      will have access to system administrator privileges and passwords
   880	      for your services.  Obviously, the system administrators will need
   881	      access, but inevitably other users will request special
   882	      privileges.  The policy should address this issue.  Restricting
   883	      privileges is one way to deal with threats from local users.  The
   884	      challenge is to balance restricting access to these to protect
   885	      security with giving people who need these privileges access so
   886	      that they can perform their tasks.  One approach that can be taken
   887	      is to grant only enough privilege to accomplish the necessary
   888	      tasks.
   889	
   890	
   891	
   892	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 16]
   893	
   894	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
   895	
   896	
   897	      Additionally, people holding special privileges should be
   898	      accountable to some authority and this should also be identified
   899	      within the site's security policy.  If the people you grant
   900	      privileges to are not accountable, you run the risk of losing
   901	      control of your system and will have difficulty managing a
   902	      compromise in security.
   903	
   904	   2.3.5  What Are The Users' Rights and Responsibilities?
   905	
   906	      The policy should incorporate a statement on the users' rights and
   907	      responsibilities concerning the use of the site's computer systems
   908	      and services.  It should be clearly stated that users are
   909	      responsible for understanding and respecting the security rules of
   910	      the systems they are using.  The following is a list of topics
   911	      that you may wish to cover in this area of the policy:
   912	
   913	         o What guidelines you have regarding resource consumption
   914	           (whether users are restricted, and if so, what the
   915	           restrictions are).
   916	         o What might constitute abuse in terms of system performance.
   917	         o Whether users are permitted to share accounts or let others
   918	           use their accounts.
   919	         o How "secret" users should keep their passwords.
   920	         o How often users should change their passwords and any other
   921	           password restrictions or requirements.
   922	         o Whether you provide backups or expect the users to create
   923	           their own.
   924	         o Disclosure of information that may be proprietary.
   925	         o Statement on Electronic Mail Privacy (Electronic
   926	           Communications Privacy Act).
   927	         o Your policy concerning controversial mail or postings to
   928	           mailing lists or discussion groups (obscenity, harassment,
   929	           etc.).
   930	         o Policy on electronic communications: mail forging, etc.
   931	
   932	      The Electronic Mail Association sponsored a white paper on the
   933	      privacy of electronic mail in companies [4].  Their basic
   934	      recommendation is that every site should have a policy on the
   935	      protection of employee privacy.  They also recommend that
   936	      organizations establish privacy policies that deal with all media,
   937	      rather than singling out electronic mail.
   938	
   939	      They suggest five criteria for evaluating any policy:
   940	
   941	         1. Does the policy comply with law and with duties to
   942	            third parties?
   943	
   944	         2. Does the policy unnecessarily compromise the interest of
   945	
   946	
   947	
   948	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 17]
   949	
   950	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
   951	
   952	
   953	            the employee, the employer or third parties?
   954	
   955	         3. Is the policy workable as a practical matter and likely to
   956	            be enforced?
   957	
   958	         4. Does the policy deal appropriately with all different
   959	            forms of communications and record keeping with the office?
   960	
   961	         5. Has the policy been announced in advance and agreed to by
   962	            all concerned?
   963	
   964	   2.3.6  What Are The Rights and Responsibilities of System
   965	          Administrators Versus Rights of Users
   966	
   967	      There is a tradeoff between a user's right to absolute privacy and
   968	      the need of system administrators to gather sufficient information
   969	      to diagnose problems.  There is also a distinction between a
   970	      system administrator's need to gather information to diagnose
   971	      problems and investigating security violations.  The policy should
   972	      specify to what degree system administrators can examine user
   973	      files to diagnose problems or for other purposes, and what rights
   974	      you grant to the users.  You may also wish to make a statement
   975	      concerning system administrators' obligation to maintaining the
   976	      privacy of information viewed under these circumstances.  A few
   977	      questions that should be answered are:
   978	
   979	         o Can an administrator monitor or read a user's files
   980	           for any reason?
   981	         o What are the liabilities?
   982	         o Do network administrators have the right to examine
   983	           network or host traffic?
   984	
   985	   2.3.7  What To Do With Sensitive Information
   986	
   987	      Before granting users access to your services, you need to
   988	      determine at what level you will provide for the security of data
   989	      on your systems.  By determining this, you are determining the
   990	      level of sensitivity of data that users should store on your
   991	      systems.  You do not want users to store very sensitive
   992	      information on a system that you are not going to secure very
   993	      well.  You need to tell users who might store sensitive
   994	      information what services, if any, are appropriate for the storage
   995	      of sensitive information.  This part should include storing of
   996	      data in different ways (disk, magnetic tape, file servers, etc.).
   997	      Your policy in this area needs to be coordinated with the policy
   998	      concerning the rights of system administrators versus users (see
   999	      section 2.3.6).
  1000	
  1001	
  1002	
  1003	
  1004	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 18]
  1005	
  1006	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1007	
  1008	
  1009	2.4  What Happens When the Policy is Violated
  1010	
  1011	   It is obvious that when any type of official policy is defined, be it
  1012	   related to computer security or not, it will eventually be broken.
  1013	   The violation may occur due to an individual's negligence, accidental
  1014	   mistake, having not been properly informed of the current policy, or
  1015	   not understanding the current policy.  It is equally possible that an
  1016	   individual (or group of individuals) may knowingly perform an act
  1017	   that is in direct violation of the defined policy.
  1018	
  1019	   When a policy violation has been detected, the immediate course of
  1020	   action should be pre-defined to ensure prompt and proper enforcement.
  1021	   An investigation should be performed to determine how and why the
  1022	   violation occurred.  Then the appropriate corrective action should be
  1023	   executed.  The type and severity of action taken varies depending on
  1024	   the type of violation that occurred.
  1025	
  1026	   2.4.1  Determining the Response to Policy Violations
  1027	
  1028	      Violations to policy may be committed by a wide variety of users.
  1029	      Some may be local users and others may be from outside the local
  1030	      environment.  Sites may find it helpful to define what it
  1031	      considers "insiders" and "outsiders" based upon administrative,
  1032	      legal or political boundaries.  These boundaries imply what type
  1033	      of action must be taken to correct the offending party; from a
  1034	      written reprimand to pressing legal charges.  So, not only do you
  1035	      need to define actions based on the type of violation, you also
  1036	      need to have a clearly defined series of actions based on the kind
  1037	      of user violating your computer security policy.  This all seems
  1038	      rather complicated, but should be addressed long before it becomes
  1039	      necessary as the result of a violation.
  1040	
  1041	      One point to remember about your policy is that proper education
  1042	      is your best defense.  For the outsiders who are using your
  1043	      computer legally, it is your responsibility to verify that these
  1044	      individuals are aware of the policies that you have set forth.
  1045	      Having this proof may assist you in the future if legal action
  1046	      becomes necessary.
  1047	
  1048	      As for users who are using your computer illegally, the problem is
  1049	      basically the same.  What type of user violated the policy and how
  1050	      and why did they do it?  Depending on the results of your
  1051	      investigation, you may just prefer to "plug" the hole in your
  1052	      computer security and chalk it up to experience.  Or if a
  1053	      significant amount of loss was incurred, you may wish to take more
  1054	      drastic action.
  1055	
  1056	
  1057	
  1058	
  1059	
  1060	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 19]
  1061	
  1062	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1063	
  1064	
  1065	   2.4.2  What to do When Local Users Violate the Policy of a Remote
  1066	          Site
  1067	
  1068	      In the event that a local user violates the security policy of a
  1069	      remote site, the local site should have a clearly defined set of
  1070	      administrative actions to take concerning that local user.  The
  1071	      site should also be prepared to protect itself against possible
  1072	      actions by the remote site.  These situations involve legal issues
  1073	      which should be addressed when forming the security policy.
  1074	
  1075	   2.4.3  Defining Contacts and Responsibilities to Outside
  1076	          Organizations
  1077	
  1078	      The local security policy should include procedures for
  1079	      interaction with outside organizations.  These include law
  1080	      enforcement agencies, other sites, external response team
  1081	      organizations (e.g., the CERT, CIAC) and various press agencies.
  1082	      The procedure should state who is authorized to make such contact
  1083	      and how it should be handled.  Some questions to be answered
  1084	      include:
  1085	
  1086	         o Who may talk to the press?
  1087	         o When do you contact law enforcement and investigative agencies?
  1088	         o If a connection is made from a remote site, is the
  1089	           system manager authorized to contact that site?
  1090	         o Can data be released?  What kind?
  1091	
  1092	      Detailed contact information should be readily available along
  1093	      with clearly defined procedures to follow.
  1094	
  1095	   2.4.4  What are the Responsibilities to our Neighbors and Other
  1096	          Internet Sites?
  1097	
  1098	      The Security Policy Working Group within the IETF is working on a
  1099	      document entitled, "Policy Guidelines for the Secure Operation of
  1100	      the Internet" [23].  It addresses the issue that the Internet is a
  1101	      cooperative venture and that sites are expected to provide mutual
  1102	      security assistance.  This should be addressed when developing a
  1103	      site's policy.  The major issue to be determined is how much
  1104	      information should be released.  This will vary from site to site
  1105	      according to the type of site (e.g., military, education,
  1106	      commercial) as well as the type of security violation that
  1107	      occurred.
  1108	
  1109	   2.4.5  Issues for Incident Handling Procedures
  1110	
  1111	      Along with statements of policy, the document being prepared
  1112	      should include procedures for incident handling.  This is covered
  1113	
  1114	
  1115	
  1116	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 20]
  1117	
  1118	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1119	
  1120	
  1121	      in detail in the next chapter.  There should be procedures
  1122	      available that cover all facets of policy violation.
  1123	
  1124	2.5  Locking In or Out
  1125	
  1126	   Whenever a site suffers an incident which may compromise computer
  1127	   security, the strategies for reacting may be influenced by two
  1128	   opposing pressures.
  1129	
  1130	   If management fears that the site is sufficiently vulnerable, it may
  1131	   choose a "Protect and Proceed" strategy.  This approach will have as
  1132	   its primary goal the protection and preservation of the site
  1133	   facilities and to provide for normalcy for its users as quickly as
  1134	   possible.  Attempts will be made to actively interfere with the
  1135	   intruder's processes, prevent further access and begin immediate
  1136	   damage assessment and recovery.  This process may involve shutting
  1137	   down the facilities, closing off access to the network, or other
  1138	   drastic measures.  The drawback is that unless the intruder is
  1139	   identified directly, they may come back into the site via a different
  1140	   path, or may attack another site.
  1141	
  1142	   The alternate approach, "Pursue and Prosecute", adopts the opposite
  1143	   philosophy and goals.  The primary goal is to allow intruders to
  1144	   continue their activities at the site until the site can identify the
  1145	   responsible persons.  This approach is endorsed by law enforcement
  1146	   agencies and prosecutors.  The drawback is that the agencies cannot
  1147	   exempt a site from possible user lawsuits if damage is done to their
  1148	   systems and data.
  1149	
  1150	   Prosecution is not the only outcome possible if the intruder is
  1151	   identified.  If the culprit is an employee or a student, the
  1152	   organization may choose to take disciplinary actions.  The computer
  1153	   security policy needs to spell out the choices and how they will be
  1154	   selected if an intruder is caught.
  1155	
  1156	   Careful consideration must be made by site management regarding their
  1157	   approach to this issue before the problem occurs.  The strategy
  1158	   adopted might depend upon each circumstance.  Or there may be a
  1159	   global policy which mandates one approach in all circumstances.  The
  1160	   pros and cons must be examined thoroughly and the users of the
  1161	   facilities must be made aware of the policy so that they understand
  1162	   their vulnerabilities no matter which approach is taken.
  1163	
  1164	   The following are checklists to help a site determine which strategy
  1165	   to adopt: "Protect and Proceed" or "Pursue and Prosecute".
  1166	
  1167	
  1168	
  1169	
  1170	
  1171	
  1172	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 21]
  1173	
  1174	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1175	
  1176	
  1177	   Protect and Proceed
  1178	
  1179	      1. If assets are not well protected.
  1180	
  1181	      2. If continued penetration could result in great
  1182	         financial risk.
  1183	
  1184	      3. If the possibility or willingness to prosecute
  1185	         is not present.
  1186	
  1187	      4. If user base is unknown.
  1188	
  1189	      5. If users are unsophisticated and their work is
  1190	         vulnerable.
  1191	
  1192	      6. If the site is vulnerable to lawsuits from users, e.g.,
  1193	         if their resources are undermined.
  1194	
  1195	   Pursue and Prosecute
  1196	
  1197	      1. If assets and systems are well protected.
  1198	
  1199	      2. If good backups are available.
  1200	
  1201	      3. If the risk to the assets is outweighed by the
  1202	         disruption caused by the present and possibly future
  1203	         penetrations.
  1204	
  1205	      4. If this is a concentrated attack occurring with great
  1206	         frequency and intensity.
  1207	
  1208	      5. If the site has a natural attraction to intruders, and
  1209	         consequently regularly attracts intruders.
  1210	
  1211	      6. If the site is willing to incur the financial (or other)
  1212	         risk to assets by allowing the penetrator continue.
  1213	
  1214	      7. If intruder access can be controlled.
  1215	
  1216	      8. If the monitoring tools are sufficiently well-developed
  1217	         to make the pursuit worthwhile.
  1218	
  1219	      9. If the support staff is sufficiently clever and knowledgable
  1220	         about the operating system, related utilities, and systems
  1221	         to make the pursuit worthwhile.
  1222	
  1223	      10. If there is willingness on the part of management to
  1224	          prosecute.
  1225	
  1226	
  1227	
  1228	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 22]
  1229	
  1230	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1231	
  1232	
  1233	      11. If the system adminitrators know in general what kind of
  1234	          evidence would lead to prosecution.
  1235	
  1236	      12. If there is established contact with knowledgeable law
  1237	          enforcement.
  1238	
  1239	      13. If there is a site representative versed in the relevant
  1240	          legal issues.
  1241	
  1242	      14. If the site is prepared for possible legal action from
  1243	          its own users if their data or systems become compromised
  1244	          during the pursuit.
  1245	
  1246	2.6  Interpreting the Policy
  1247	
  1248	   It is important to define who will interpret the policy.  This could
  1249	   be an individual or a committee.  No matter how well written, the
  1250	   policy will require interpretation from time to time and this body
  1251	   would serve to review, interpret, and revise the policy as needed.
  1252	
  1253	2.7  Publicizing the Policy
  1254	
  1255	   Once the site security policy has been written and established, a
  1256	   vigorous process should be engaged to ensure that the policy
  1257	   statement is widely and thoroughly disseminated and discussed.  A
  1258	   mailing of the policy should not be considered sufficient.  A period
  1259	   for comments should be allowed before the policy becomes effective to
  1260	   ensure that all affected users have a chance to state their reactions
  1261	   and discuss any unforeseen ramifications.  Ideally, the policy should
  1262	   strike a balance between protection and productivity.
  1263	
  1264	   Meetings should be held to elicit these comments, and also to ensure
  1265	   that the policy is correctly understood.  (Policy promulgators are
  1266	   not necessarily noted for their skill with the language.)  These
  1267	   meetings should involve higher management as well as line employees.
  1268	   Security is a collective effort.
  1269	
  1270	   In addition to the initial efforts to publicize the policy, it is
  1271	   essential for the site to maintain a continual awareness of its
  1272	   computer security policy.  Current users may need periodic reminders
  1273	   New users should have the policy included as part of their site
  1274	   introduction packet.  As a condition for using the site facilities,
  1275	   it may be advisable to have them sign a statement that they have read
  1276	   and understood the policy.  Should any of these users require legal
  1277	   action for serious policy violations, this signed statement might
  1278	   prove to be a valuable aid.
  1279	
  1280	
  1281	
  1282	
  1283	
  1284	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 23]
  1285	
  1286	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1287	
  1288	
  1289	3.  Establishing Procedures to Prevent Security Problems
  1290	
  1291	   The security policy defines what needs to be protected.  This section
  1292	   discusses security procedures which specify what steps will be used
  1293	   to carry out the security policy.
  1294	
  1295	3.1  Security Policy Defines What Needs to be Protected
  1296	
  1297	   The security policy defines the WHAT's: what needs to be protected,
  1298	   what is most important, what the priorities are, and what the general
  1299	   approach to dealing with security problems should be.
  1300	
  1301	   The security policy by itself doesn't say HOW things are protected.
  1302	   That is the role of security procedures, which this section
  1303	   discusses.  The security policy should be a high level document,
  1304	   giving general strategy.  The security procedures need to set out, in
  1305	   detail, the precise steps your site will take to protect itself.
  1306	
  1307	   The security policy should include a general risk assessment of the
  1308	   types of threats a site is mostly likely to face and the consequences
  1309	   of those threats (see section 2.2).  Part of doing a risk assessment
  1310	   will include creating a general list of assets that should be
  1311	   protected (section 2.2.2).  This information is critical in devising
  1312	   cost-effective procedures.
  1313	
  1314	   It is often tempting to start creating security procedures by
  1315	   deciding on different mechanisms first: "our site should have logging
  1316	   on all hosts, call-back modems, and smart cards for all users."  This
  1317	   approach could lead to some areas that have too much protection for
  1318	   the risk they face, and other areas that aren't protected enough.
  1319	   Starting with the security policy and the risks it outlines should
  1320	   ensure that the procedures provide the right level of protect for all
  1321	   assets.
  1322	
  1323	3.2  Identifing Possible Problems
  1324	
  1325	   To determine risk, vulnerabilities must be identified.  Part of the
  1326	   purpose of the policy is to aid in shoring up the vulnerabilities and
  1327	   thus to decrease the risk in as many areas as possible.  Several of
  1328	   the more popular problem areas are presented in sections below.  This
  1329	   list is by no means complete.  In addition, each site is likely to
  1330	   have a few unique vulnerabilities.
  1331	
  1332	   3.2.1  Access Points
  1333	
  1334	      Access points are typically used for entry by unauthorized users.
  1335	      Having many access points increases the risk of access to an
  1336	      organization's computer and network facilities.
  1337	
  1338	
  1339	
  1340	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 24]
  1341	
  1342	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1343	
  1344	
  1345	      Network links to networks outside the organization allow access
  1346	      into the organization for all others connected to that external
  1347	      network.  A network link typically provides access to a large
  1348	      number of network services, and each service has a potential to be
  1349	      compromised.
  1350	
  1351	      Dialup lines, depending on their configuration, may provide access
  1352	      merely to a login port of a single system.  If connected to a
  1353	      terminal server, the dialup line may give access to the entire
  1354	      network.
  1355	
  1356	      Terminal servers themselves can be a source of problem.  Many
  1357	      terminal servers do not require any kind of authentication.
  1358	      Intruders often use terminal servers to disguise their actions,
  1359	      dialing in on a local phone and then using the terminal server to
  1360	      go out to the local network.  Some terminal servers are configured
  1361	      so that intruders can TELNET [19] in from outside the network, and
  1362	      then TELNET back out again, again serving to make it difficult to
  1363	      trace them.
  1364	
  1365	   3.2.2  Misconfigured Systems
  1366	
  1367	      Misconfigured systems form a large percentage of security holes.
  1368	      Today's operating systems and their associated software have
  1369	      become so complex that understanding how the system works has
  1370	      become a full-time job.  Often, systems managers will be non-
  1371	      specialists chosen from the current organization's staff.
  1372	
  1373	      Vendors are also partly responsible for misconfigured systems. To
  1374	      make the system installation process easier, vendors occasionally
  1375	      choose initial configurations that are not secure in all
  1376	      environments.
  1377	
  1378	   3.2.3  Software Bugs
  1379	
  1380	      Software will never be bug free.  Publicly known security bugs are
  1381	      common methods of unauthorized entry.  Part of the solution to
  1382	      this problem is to be aware of the security problems and to update
  1383	      the software when problems are detected.  When bugs are found,
  1384	      they should be reported to the vendor so that a solution to the
  1385	      problem can be implemented and distributed.
  1386	
  1387	   3.2.4  "Insider" Threats
  1388	
  1389	      An insider to the organization may be a considerable threat to the
  1390	      security of the computer systems.  Insiders often have direct
  1391	      access to the computer and network hardware components.  The
  1392	      ability to access the components of a system makes most systems
  1393	
  1394	
  1395	
  1396	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 25]
  1397	
  1398	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1399	
  1400	
  1401	      easier to compromise.  Most desktop workstations can be easily
  1402	      manipulated so that they grant privileged access.  Access to a
  1403	      local area network provides the ability to view possibly sensitive
  1404	      data traversing the network.
  1405	
  1406	3.3  Choose Controls to Protect Assets in a Cost-Effective Way
  1407	
  1408	   After establishing what is to be protected, and assessing the risks
  1409	   these assets face, it is necessary to decide how to implement the
  1410	   controls which protect these assets.  The controls and protection
  1411	   mechanisms should be selected in a way so as to adequately counter
  1412	   the threats found during risk assessment, and to implement those
  1413	   controls in a cost effective manner.  It makes little sense to spend
  1414	   an exorbitant sum of money and overly constrict the user base if the
  1415	   risk of exposure is very small.
  1416	
  1417	   3.3.1  Choose the Right Set of Controls
  1418	
  1419	      The controls that are selected represent the physical embodiment
  1420	      of your security policy.  They are the first and primary line of
  1421	      defense in the protection of your assets.  It is therefore most
  1422	      important to ensure that the controls that you select are the
  1423	      right set of controls.  If the major threat to your system is
  1424	      outside penetrators, it probably doesn't make much sense to use
  1425	      biometric devices to authenticate your regular system users.  On
  1426	      the other hand, if the major threat is unauthorized use of
  1427	      computing resources by regular system users, you'll probably want
  1428	      to establish very rigorous automated accounting procedures.
  1429	
  1430	   3.3.2  Use Common Sense
  1431	
  1432	      Common sense is the most appropriate tool that can be used to
  1433	      establish your security policy.  Elaborate security schemes and
  1434	      mechanisms are impressive, and they do have their place, yet there
  1435	      is little point in investing money and time on an elaborate
  1436	      implementation scheme if the simple controls are forgotten.  For
  1437	      example, no matter how elaborate a system you put into place on
  1438	      top of existing security controls, a single user with a poor
  1439	      password can still leave your system open to attack.
  1440	
  1441	3.4  Use Multiple Strategies to Protect Assets
  1442	
  1443	   Another method of protecting assets is to use multiple strategies.
  1444	   In this way, if one strategy fails or is circumvented, another
  1445	   strategy comes into play to continue protecting the asset.  By using
  1446	   several simpler strategies, a system can often be made more secure
  1447	   than if one very sophisticated method were used in its place.  For
  1448	   example, dial-back modems can be used in conjunction with traditional
  1449	
  1450	
  1451	
  1452	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 26]
  1453	
  1454	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1455	
  1456	
  1457	   logon mechanisms.  Many similar approaches could be devised that
  1458	   provide several levels of protection for assets.  However, it's very
  1459	   easy to go overboard with extra mechanisms.  One must keep in mind
  1460	   exactly what it is that needs to be protected.
  1461	
  1462	3.5  Physical Security
  1463	
  1464	   It is a given in computer security if the system itself is not
  1465	   physically secure, nothing else about the system can be considered
  1466	   secure.  With physical access to a machine, an intruder can halt the
  1467	   machine, bring it back up in privileged mode, replace or alter the
  1468	   disk, plant Trojan horse programs (see section 2.13.9.2), or take any
  1469	   number of other undesirable (and hard to prevent) actions.
  1470	
  1471	   Critical communications links, important servers, and other key
  1472	   machines should be located in physically secure areas.  Some security
  1473	   systems (such as Kerberos) require that the machine be physically
  1474	   secure.
  1475	
  1476	   If you cannot physically secure machines, care should be taken about
  1477	   trusting those machines.  Sites should consider limiting access from
  1478	   non-secure machines to more secure machines.  In particular, allowing
  1479	   trusted access (e.g., the BSD Unix remote commands such as rsh) from
  1480	   these kinds of hosts is particularly risky.
  1481	
  1482	   For machines that seem or are intended to be physically secure, care
  1483	   should be taken about who has access to the machines.  Remember that
  1484	   custodial and maintenance staff often have keys to rooms.
  1485	
  1486	3.6   Procedures to Recognize Unauthorized Activity
  1487	
  1488	   Several simple procedures can be used to detect most unauthorized
  1489	   uses of a computer system.  These procedures use tools provided with
  1490	   the operating system by the vendor, or tools publicly available from
  1491	   other sources.
  1492	
  1493	   3.6.1  Monitoring System Use
  1494	
  1495	      System monitoring can be done either by a system administrator, or
  1496	      by software written for the purpose.  Monitoring a system involves
  1497	      looking at several parts of the system and searching for anything
  1498	      unusual.  Some of the easier ways to do this are described in this
  1499	      section.
  1500	
  1501	      The most important thing about monitoring system use is that it be
  1502	      done on a regular basis.  Picking one day out of the month to
  1503	      monitor the system is pointless, since a security breach can be
  1504	      isolated to a matter of hours.  Only by maintaining a constant
  1505	
  1506	
  1507	
  1508	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 27]
  1509	
  1510	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1511	
  1512	
  1513	      vigil can you expect to detect security violations in time to
  1514	      react to them.
  1515	
  1516	   3.6.2  Tools for Monitoring the System
  1517	
  1518	      This section describes tools and methods for monitoring a system
  1519	      against unauthorized access and use.
  1520	
  1521	      3.6.2.1  Logging
  1522	
  1523	         Most operating systems store numerous bits of information in
  1524	         log files.  Examination of these log files on a regular basis
  1525	         is often the first line of defense in detecting unauthorized
  1526	         use of the system.
  1527	
  1528	            - Compare lists of currently logged in users and past
  1529	              login histories.  Most users typically log in and out
  1530	              at roughly the same time each day.  An account logged
  1531	              in outside the "normal" time for the account may be in
  1532	              use by an intruder.
  1533	
  1534	            - Many systems maintain accounting records for billing
  1535	              purposes.  These records can also be used to determine
  1536	              usage patterns for the system; unusual accounting records
  1537	              may indicate unauthorized use of the system.
  1538	
  1539	            - System logging facilities, such as the UNIX "syslog"
  1540	              utility, should be checked for unusual error messages
  1541	              from system software.  For example, a large number of
  1542	              failed login attempts in a short period of time may
  1543	              indicate someone trying to guess passwords.
  1544	
  1545	            - Operating system commands which list currently executing
  1546	              processes can be used to detect users running programs
  1547	              they are not authorized to use, as well as to detect
  1548	              unauthorized programs which have been started by an
  1549	              intruder.
  1550	
  1551	      3.6.2.2  Monitoring Software
  1552	
  1553	         Other monitoring tools can easily be constructed using standard
  1554	         operating system software, by using several, often unrelated,
  1555	         programs together.  For example, checklists of file ownerships
  1556	         and permission settings can be constructed (for example, with
  1557	         "ls" and "find" on UNIX) and stored off-line.  These lists can
  1558	         then be reconstructed periodically and compared against the
  1559	         master checklist (on UNIX, by using the "diff" utility).
  1560	         Differences may indicate that unauthorized modifications have
  1561	
  1562	
  1563	
  1564	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 28]
  1565	
  1566	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1567	
  1568	
  1569	         been made to the system.
  1570	
  1571	         Still other tools are available from third-party vendors and
  1572	         public software distribution sites.  Section 3.9.9 lists
  1573	         several sources from which you can learn what tools are
  1574	         available and how to get them.
  1575	
  1576	      3.6.2.3  Other Tools
  1577	
  1578	         Other tools can also be used to monitor systems for security
  1579	         violations, although this is not their primary purpose.  For
  1580	         example, network monitors can be used to detect and log
  1581	         connections from unknown sites.
  1582	
  1583	   3.6.3  Vary the Monitoring Schedule
  1584	
  1585	      The task of system monitoring is not as daunting as it may seem.
  1586	      System administrators can execute many of the commands used for
  1587	      monitoring periodically throughout the day during idle moments
  1588	      (e.g., while talking on the telephone), rather than spending fixed
  1589	      periods of each day monitoring the system.  By executing the
  1590	      commands frequently, you will rapidly become used to seeing
  1591	      "normal" output, and will easily spot things which are out of the
  1592	      ordinary.  In addition, by running various monitoring commands at
  1593	      different times throughout the day, you make it hard for an
  1594	      intruder to predict your actions.  For example, if an intruder
  1595	      knows that each day at 5:00 p.m. the system is checked to see that
  1596	      everyone has logged off, he will simply wait until after the check
  1597	      has completed before logging in.  But the intruder cannot guess
  1598	      when a system administrator might type a command to display all
  1599	      logged-in users, and thus he runs a much greater risk of
  1600	      detection.
  1601	
  1602	      Despite the advantages that regular system monitoring provides,
  1603	      some intruders will be aware of the standard logging mechanisms in
  1604	      use on systems they are attacking.  They will actively pursue and
  1605	      attempt to disable monitoring mechanisms.  Regular monitoring
  1606	      therefore is useful in detecting intruders, but does not provide
  1607	      any guarantee that your system is secure, nor should monitoring be
  1608	      considered an infallible method of detecting unauthorized use.
  1609	
  1610	3.7  Define Actions to Take When Unauthorized Activity is Suspected
  1611	
  1612	      Sections 2.4 and 2.5 discussed the course of action a site should
  1613	      take when it suspects its systems are being abused.  The computer
  1614	      security policy should state the general approach towards dealing
  1615	      with these problems.
  1616	
  1617	
  1618	
  1619	
  1620	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 29]
  1621	
  1622	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1623	
  1624	
  1625	      The procedures for dealing with these types of problems should be
  1626	      written down.  Who has authority to decide what actions will be
  1627	      taken?  Should law enforcement be involved?  Should your
  1628	      organization cooperate with other sites in trying to track down an
  1629	      intruder?  Answers to all the questions in section 2.4 should be
  1630	      part of the incident handling procedures.
  1631	
  1632	      Whether you decide to lock out or pursue intruders, you should
  1633	      have tools and procedures ready to apply.  It is best to work up
  1634	      these tools and procedures before you need them.  Don't wait until
  1635	      an intruder is on your system to figure out how to track the
  1636	      intruder's actions; you will be busy enough if an intruder
  1637	      strikes.
  1638	
  1639	3.8  Communicating Security Policy
  1640	
  1641	   Security policies, in order to be effective, must be communicated to
  1642	   both the users of the system and the system maintainers.  This
  1643	   section describes what these people should be told, and how to tell
  1644	   them.
  1645	
  1646	   3.8.1  Educating the Users
  1647	
  1648	      Users should be made aware of how the computer systems are
  1649	      expected to be used, and how to protect themselves from
  1650	      unauthorized users.
  1651	
  1652	      3.8.1.1  Proper Account/Workstation Use
  1653	
  1654	         All users should be informed about what is considered the
  1655	         "proper" use of their account or workstation ("proper" use is
  1656	         discussed in section 2.3.2).  This can most easily be done at
  1657	         the time a user receives their account, by giving them a policy
  1658	         statement.  Proper use policies typically dictate things such
  1659	         as whether or not the account or workstation may be used for
  1660	         personal activities (such as checkbook balancing or letter
  1661	         writing), whether profit-making activities are allowed, whether
  1662	         game playing is permitted, and so on.  These policy statements
  1663	         may also be used to summarize how the computer facility is
  1664	         licensed and what software licenses are held by the
  1665	         institution; for example, many universities have educational
  1666	         licenses which explicitly prohibit commercial uses of the
  1667	         system.  A more complete list of items to consider when writing
  1668	         a policy statement is given in section 2.3.
  1669	
  1670	      3.8.1.2  Account/Workstation Management Procedures
  1671	
  1672	         Each user should be told how to properly manage their account
  1673	
  1674	
  1675	
  1676	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 30]
  1677	
  1678	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1679	
  1680	
  1681	         and workstation.  This includes explaining how to protect files
  1682	         stored on the system, how to log out or lock the terminal or
  1683	         workstation, and so on.  Much of this information is typically
  1684	         covered in the "beginning user" documentation provided by the
  1685	         operating system vendor, although many sites elect to
  1686	         supplement this material with local information.
  1687	
  1688	         If your site offers dial-up modem access to the computer
  1689	         systems, special care must be taken to inform users of the
  1690	         security problems inherent in providing this access.  Issues
  1691	         such as making sure to log out before hanging up the modem
  1692	         should be covered when the user is initially given dial-up
  1693	         access.
  1694	
  1695	         Likewise, access to the systems via local and wide-area
  1696	         networks presents its own set of security problems which users
  1697	         should be made aware of.  Files which grant "trusted host" or
  1698	         "trusted user" status to remote systems and users should be
  1699	         carefully explained.
  1700	
  1701	      3.8.1.3  Determining Account Misuse
  1702	
  1703	         Users should be told how to detect unauthorized access to their
  1704	         account.  If the system prints the last login time when a user
  1705	         logs in, he or she should be told to check that time and note
  1706	         whether or not it agrees with the last time he or she actually
  1707	         logged in.
  1708	
  1709	         Command interpreters on some systems (e.g., the UNIX C shell)
  1710	         maintain histories of the last several commands executed.
  1711	         Users should check these histories to be sure someone has not
  1712	         executed other commands with their account.
  1713	
  1714	      3.8.1.4  Problem Reporting Procedures
  1715	
  1716	         A procedure should be developed to enable users to report
  1717	         suspected misuse of their accounts or other misuse they may
  1718	         have noticed.  This can be done either by providing the name
  1719	         and telephone number of a system administrator who manages
  1720	         security of the computer system, or by creating an electronic
  1721	         mail address (e.g., "security") to which users can address
  1722	         their problems.
  1723	
  1724	   3.8.2  Educating the Host Administrators
  1725	
  1726	      In many organizations, computer systems are administered by a wide
  1727	      variety of people.  These administrators must know how to protect
  1728	      their own systems from attack and unauthorized use, as well as how
  1729	
  1730	
  1731	
  1732	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 31]
  1733	
  1734	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1735	
  1736	
  1737	      to communicate successful penetration of their systems to other
  1738	      administrators as a warning.
  1739	
  1740	      3.8.2.1  Account Management Procedures
  1741	
  1742	         Care must be taken when installing accounts on the system in
  1743	         order to make them secure.  When installing a system from
  1744	         distribution media, the password file should be examined for
  1745	         "standard" accounts provided by the vendor.  Many vendors
  1746	         provide accounts for use by system services or field service
  1747	         personnel.  These accounts typically have either no password or
  1748	         one which is common knowledge.  These accounts should be given
  1749	         new passwords if they are needed, or disabled or deleted from
  1750	         the system if they are not.
  1751	
  1752	         Accounts without passwords are generally very dangerous since
  1753	         they allow anyone to access the system.  Even accounts which do
  1754	         not execute a command interpreter (e.g., accounts which exist
  1755	         only to see who is logged in to the system) can be compromised
  1756	         if set up incorrectly.  A related concept, that of "anonymous"
  1757	         file transfer (FTP) [20], allows users from all over the
  1758	         network to access your system to retrieve files from (usually)
  1759	         a protected disk area.  You should carefully weigh the benefits
  1760	         that an account without a password provides against the
  1761	         security risks of providing such access to your system.
  1762	
  1763	         If the operating system provides a "shadow" password facility
  1764	         which stores passwords in a separate file accessible only to
  1765	         privileged users, this facility should be used.  System V UNIX,
  1766	         SunOS 4.0 and above, and versions of Berkeley UNIX after 4.3BSD
  1767	         Tahoe, as well as others, provide this feature.  It protects
  1768	         passwords by hiding their encrypted values from unprivileged
  1769	         users.  This prevents an attacker from copying your password
  1770	         file to his or her machine and then attempting to break the
  1771	         passwords at his or her leisure.
  1772	
  1773	         Keep track of who has access to privileged user accounts (e.g.,
  1774	         "root" on UNIX or "MAINT" on VMS).  Whenever a privileged user
  1775	         leaves the organization or no longer has need of the privileged
  1776	         account, the passwords on all privileged accounts should be
  1777	         changed.
  1778	
  1779	      3.8.2.2  Configuration Management Procedures
  1780	
  1781	         When installing a system from the distribution media or when
  1782	         installing third-party software, it is important to check the
  1783	         installation carefully.  Many installation procedures assume a
  1784	         "trusted" site, and hence will install files with world write
  1785	
  1786	
  1787	
  1788	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 32]
  1789	
  1790	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1791	
  1792	
  1793	         permission enabled, or otherwise compromise the security of
  1794	         files.
  1795	
  1796	         Network services should also be examined carefully when first
  1797	         installed.  Many vendors provide default network permission
  1798	         files which imply that all outside hosts are to be "trusted",
  1799	         which is rarely the case when connected to wide-area networks
  1800	         such as the Internet.
  1801	
  1802	         Many intruders collect information on the vulnerabilities of
  1803	         particular system versions.  The older a system, the more
  1804	         likely it is that there are security problems in that version
  1805	         which have since been fixed by the vendor in a later release.
  1806	         For this reason, it is important to weigh the risks of not
  1807	         upgrading to a new operating system release (thus leaving
  1808	         security holes unplugged) against the cost of upgrading to the
  1809	         new software (possibly breaking third-party software, etc.).
  1810	         Bug fixes from the vendor should be weighed in a similar
  1811	         fashion, with the added note that "security" fixes from a
  1812	         vendor usually address fairly serious security problems.
  1813	
  1814	         Other bug fixes, received via network mailing lists and the
  1815	         like, should usually be installed, but not without careful
  1816	         examination.  Never install a bug fix unless you're sure you
  1817	         know what the consequences of the fix are - there's always the
  1818	         possibility that an intruder has suggested a "fix" which
  1819	         actually gives him or her access to your system.
  1820	
  1821	      3.8.2.3  Recovery Procedures - Backups
  1822	
  1823	         It is impossible to overemphasize the need for a good backup
  1824	         strategy.  File system backups not only protect you in the
  1825	         event of hardware failure or accidental deletions, but they
  1826	         also protect you against unauthorized changes made by an
  1827	         intruder.  Without a copy of your data the way it's "supposed"
  1828	         to be, it can be difficult to undo something an attacker has
  1829	         done.
  1830	
  1831	         Backups, especially if run daily, can also be useful in
  1832	         providing a history of an intruder's activities.  Looking
  1833	         through old backups can establish when your system was first
  1834	         penetrated.  Intruders may leave files around which, although
  1835	         deleted later, are captured on the backup tapes.  Backups can
  1836	         also be used to document an intruder's activities to law
  1837	         enforcement agencies if necessary.
  1838	
  1839	         A good backup strategy will dump the entire system to tape at
  1840	         least once a month.  Partial (or "incremental") dumps should be
  1841	
  1842	
  1843	
  1844	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 33]
  1845	
  1846	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1847	
  1848	
  1849	         done at least twice a week, and ideally they should be done
  1850	         daily.  Commands specifically designed for performing file
  1851	         system backups (e.g., UNIX "dump" or VMS "BACKUP") should be
  1852	         used in preference to other file copying commands, since these
  1853	         tools are designed with the express intent of restoring a
  1854	         system to a known state.
  1855	
  1856	      3.8.2.4  Problem Reporting Procedures
  1857	
  1858	         As with users, system administrators should have a defined
  1859	         procedure for reporting security problems.  In large
  1860	         installations, this is often done by creating an electronic
  1861	         mail alias which contains the names of all system
  1862	         administrators in the organization.  Other methods include
  1863	         setting up some sort of response team similar to the CERT, or
  1864	         establishing a "hotline" serviced by an existing support group.
  1865	
  1866	3.9  Resources to Prevent Security Breaches
  1867	
  1868	   This section discusses software, hardware, and procedural resources
  1869	   that can be used to support your site security policy.
  1870	
  1871	   3.9.1  Network Connections and Firewalls
  1872	
  1873	      A "firewall" is put in place in a building to provide a point of
  1874	      resistance to the entry of flames into another area.  Similarly, a
  1875	      secretary's desk and reception area provides a point of
  1876	      controlling access to other office spaces.  This same technique
  1877	      can be applied to a computer site, particularly as it pertains to
  1878	      network connections.
  1879	
  1880	      Some sites will be connected only to other sites within the same
  1881	      organization and will not have the ability to connect to other
  1882	      networks.  Sites such as these are less susceptible to threats
  1883	      from outside their own organization, although intrusions may still
  1884	      occur via paths such as dial-up modems.  On the other hand, many
  1885	      other organizations will be connected to other sites via much
  1886	      larger networks, such as the Internet.  These sites are
  1887	      susceptible to the entire range of threats associated with a
  1888	      networked environment.
  1889	
  1890	      The risks of connecting to outside networks must be weighed
  1891	      against the benefits.  It may be desirable to limit connection to
  1892	      outside networks to those hosts which do not store sensitive
  1893	      material, keeping "vital" machines (such as those which maintain
  1894	      company payroll or inventory systems) isolated.  If there is a
  1895	      need to participate in a Wide Area Network (WAN), consider
  1896	      restricting all access to your local network through a single
  1897	
  1898	
  1899	
  1900	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 34]
  1901	
  1902	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1903	
  1904	
  1905	      system.  That is, all access to or from your own local network
  1906	      must be made through a single host computer that acts as a
  1907	      firewall between you and the outside world.  This firewall system
  1908	      should be rigorously controlled and password protected, and
  1909	      external users accessing it should also be constrained by
  1910	      restricting the functionality available to remote users.  By using
  1911	      this approach, your site could relax some of the internal security
  1912	      controls on your local net, but still be afforded the protection
  1913	      of a rigorously controlled host front end.
  1914	
  1915	      Note that even with a firewall system, compromise of the firewall
  1916	      could result in compromise of the network behind the firewall.
  1917	      Work has been done in some areas to construct a firewall which
  1918	      even when compromised, still protects the local network [6,
  1919	      CHESWICK].
  1920	
  1921	   3.9.2  Confidentiality
  1922	
  1923	      Confidentiality, the act of keeping things hidden or secret, is
  1924	      one of the primary goals of computer security practitioners.
  1925	      Several mechanisms are provided by most modern operating systems
  1926	      to enable users to control the dissemination of information.
  1927	      Depending upon where you work, you may have a site where
  1928	      everything is protected, or a site where all information is
  1929	      usually regarded as public, or something in-between.  Most sites
  1930	      lean toward the in-between, at least until some penetration has
  1931	      occurred.
  1932	
  1933	      Generally, there are three instances in which information is
  1934	      vulnerable to disclosure: when the information is stored on a
  1935	      computer system, when the information is in transit to another
  1936	      system (on the network), and when the information is stored on
  1937	      backup tapes.
  1938	
  1939	      The first of these cases is controlled by file permissions, access
  1940	      control lists, and other similar mechanisms.  The last can be
  1941	      controlled by restricting access to the backup tapes (by locking
  1942	      them in a safe, for example).  All three cases can be helped by
  1943	      using encryption mechanisms.
  1944	
  1945	      3.9.2.1  Encryption (hardware and software)
  1946	
  1947	         Encryption is the process of taking information that exists in
  1948	         some readable form and converting it into a non-readable form.
  1949	         There are several types of commercially available encryption
  1950	         packages in both hardware and software forms.  Hardware
  1951	         encryption engines have the advantage that they are much faster
  1952	         than the software equivalent, yet because they are faster, they
  1953	
  1954	
  1955	
  1956	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 35]
  1957	
  1958	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  1959	
  1960	
  1961	         are of greater potential benefit to an attacker who wants to
  1962	         execute a brute-force attack on your encrypted information.
  1963	
  1964	         The advantage of using encryption is that, even if other access
  1965	         control mechanisms (passwords, file permissions, etc.) are
  1966	         compromised by an intruder, the data is still unusable.
  1967	         Naturally, encryption keys and the like should be protected at
  1968	         least as well as account passwords.
  1969	
  1970	         Information in transit (over a network) may be vulnerable to
  1971	         interception as well.  Several solutions to this exist, ranging
  1972	         from simply encrypting files before transferring them (end-to-
  1973	         end encryption) to special network hardware which encrypts
  1974	         everything it sends without user intervention (secure links).
  1975	         The Internet as a whole does not use secure links, thus end-
  1976	         to-end encryption must be used if encryption is desired across
  1977	         the Internet.
  1978	
  1979	         3.9.2.1.1  Data Encryption Standard (DES)
  1980	
  1981	            DES is perhaps the most widely used data encryption
  1982	            mechanism today.  Many hardware and software implementations
  1983	            exist, and some commercial computers are provided with a
  1984	            software version.  DES transforms plain text information
  1985	            into encrypted data (or ciphertext) by means of a special
  1986	            algorithm and "seed" value called a key.  So long as the key
  1987	            is retained (or remembered) by the original user, the
  1988	            ciphertext can be restored to the original plain text.
  1989	
  1990	            One of the pitfalls of all encryption systems is the need to
  1991	            remember the key under which a thing was encrypted (this is
  1992	            not unlike the password problem discussed elsewhere in this
  1993	            document).  If the key is written down, it becomes less
  1994	            secure.  If forgotten, there is little (if any) hope of
  1995	            recovering the original data.
  1996	
  1997	            Most UNIX systems provide a DES command that enables a user
  1998	            to encrypt data using the DES algorithm.
  1999	
  2000	         3.9.2.1.2  Crypt
  2001	
  2002	            Similar to the DES command, the UNIX "crypt" command allows
  2003	            a user to encrypt data.  Unfortunately, the algorithm used
  2004	            by "crypt" is very insecure (based on the World War II
  2005	            "Enigma" device), and files encrypted with this command can
  2006	            be decrypted easily in a matter of a few hours.  Generally,
  2007	            use of the "crypt" command should be avoided for any but the
  2008	            most trivial encryption tasks.
  2009	
  2010	
  2011	
  2012	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 36]
  2013	
  2014	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  2015	
  2016	
  2017	      3.9.2.2  Privacy Enhanced Mail
  2018	
  2019	         Electronic mail normally transits the network in the clear
  2020	         (i.e., anyone can read it).  This is obviously not the optimal
  2021	         solution.  Privacy enhanced mail provides a means to
  2022	         automatically encrypt electronic mail messages so that a person
  2023	         eavesdropping at a mail distribution node is not (easily)
  2024	         capable of reading them.  Several privacy enhanced mail
  2025	         packages are currently being developed and deployed on the
  2026	         Internet.
  2027	
  2028	         The Internet Activities Board Privacy Task Force has defined a
  2029	         draft standard, elective protocol for use in implementing
  2030	         privacy enhanced mail.  This protocol is defined in RFCs 1113,
  2031	         1114, and 1115 [7,8,9].  Please refer to the current edition of
  2032	         the "IAB Official Protocol Standards" (currently, RFC 1200
  2033	         [21]) for the standardization state and status of these
  2034	         protocols.
  2035	
  2036	   3.9.3  Origin Authentication
  2037	
  2038	      We mostly take it on faith that the header of an electronic mail
  2039	      message truly indicates the originator of a message.  However, it
  2040	      iseasy to "spoof", or forge the source of a mail message.  Origin
  2041	      authentication provides a means to be certain of the originator of
  2042	      a message or other object in the same way that a Notary Public
  2043	      assures a signature on a legal document.  This is done by means of
  2044	      a "Public Key" cryptosystem.
  2045	
  2046	      A public key cryptosystem differs from a private key cryptosystem
  2047	      in several ways.  First, a public key system uses two keys, a
  2048	      Public Key that anyone can use (hence the name) and a Private Key
  2049	      that only the originator of a message uses.  The originator uses
  2050	      the private key to encrypt the message (as in DES).  The receiver,
  2051	      who has obtained the public key for the originator, may then
  2052	      decrypt the message.
  2053	
  2054	      In this scheme, the public key is used to authenticate the
  2055	      originator's use of his or her private key, and hence the identity
  2056	      of the originator is more rigorously proven.  The most widely
  2057	      known implementation of a public key cryptosystem is the RSA
  2058	      system [26].  The Internet standard for privacy enhanced mail
  2059	      makes use of the RSA system.
  2060	
  2061	   3.9.4  Information Integrity
  2062	
  2063	      Information integrity refers to the state of information such that
  2064	      it is complete, correct, and unchanged from the last time in which
  2065	
  2066	
  2067	
  2068	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 37]
  2069	
  2070	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  2071	
  2072	
  2073	      it was verified to be in an "integral" state.  The value of
  2074	      information integrity to a site will vary.  For example, it is
  2075	      more important for military and government installations to
  2076	      prevent the "disclosure" of classified information, whether it is
  2077	      right or wrong.  A bank, on the other hand, is far more concerned
  2078	      with whether the account information maintained for its customers
  2079	      is complete and accurate.
  2080	
  2081	      Numerous computer system mechanisms, as well as procedural
  2082	      controls, have an influence on the integrity of system
  2083	      information.  Traditional access control mechanisms maintain
  2084	      controls over who can access system information.  These mechanisms
  2085	      alone are not sufficient in some cases to provide the degree of
  2086	      integrity required.  Some other mechanisms are briefly discussed
  2087	      below.
  2088	
  2089	      It should be noted that there are other aspects to maintaining
  2090	      system integrity besides these mechanisms, such as two-person
  2091	      controls, and integrity validation procedures.  These are beyond
  2092	      the scope of this document.
  2093	
  2094	      3.9.4.1  Checksums
  2095	
  2096	         Easily the simplest mechanism, a simple checksum routine can
  2097	         compute a value for a system file and compare it with the last
  2098	         known value.  If the two are equal, the file is probably
  2099	         unchanged.  If not, the file has been changed by some unknown
  2100	         means.
  2101	
  2102	         Though it is the easiest to implement, the checksum scheme
  2103	         suffers from a serious failing in that it is not very
  2104	         sophisticated and a determined attacker could easily add enough
  2105	         characters to the file to eventually obtain the correct value.
  2106	
  2107	         A specific type of checksum, called a CRC checksum, is
  2108	         considerably more robust than a simple checksum.  It is only
  2109	         slightly more difficult to implement and provides a better
  2110	         degree of catching errors.  It too, however, suffers from the
  2111	         possibility of compromise by an attacker.
  2112	
  2113	         Checksums may be used to detect the altering of information.
  2114	         However, they do not actively guard against changes being made.
  2115	         For this, other mechanisms such as access controls and
  2116	         encryption should be used.
  2117	
  2118	
  2119	
  2120	
  2121	
  2122	
  2123	
  2124	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 38]
  2125	
  2126	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  2127	
  2128	
  2129	      3.9.4.2  Cryptographic Checksums
  2130	
  2131	         Cryptographic checksums (also called cryptosealing) involve
  2132	         breaking a file up into smaller chunks, calculating a (CRC)
  2133	         checksum for each chunk, and adding the CRCs together.
  2134	         Depending upon the exact algorithm used, this can result in a
  2135	         nearly unbreakable method of determining whether a file has
  2136	         been changed.  This mechanism suffers from the fact that it is
  2137	         sometimes computationally intensive and may be prohibitive
  2138	         except in cases where the utmost integrity protection is
  2139	         desired.
  2140	
  2141	         Another related mechanism, called a one-way hash function (or a
  2142	         Manipulation Detection Code (MDC)) can also be used to uniquely
  2143	         identify a file.  The idea behind these functions is that no
  2144	         two inputs can produce the same output, thus a modified file
  2145	         will not have the same hash value.  One-way hash functions can
  2146	         be implemented efficiently on a wide variety of systems, making
  2147	         unbreakable integrity checks possible.  (Snefru, a one-way hash
  2148	         function available via USENET as well as the Internet is just
  2149	         one example of an efficient one-way hash function.) [10]
  2150	
  2151	   3.9.5  Limiting Network Access
  2152	
  2153	      The dominant network protocols in use on the Internet, IP (RFC
  2154	      791) [11], TCP (RFC 793) [12], and UDP (RFC 768) [13], carry
  2155	      certain control information which can be used to restrict access
  2156	      to certain hosts or networks within an organization.
  2157	
  2158	      The IP packet header contains the network addresses of both the
  2159	      sender and recipient of the packet.  Further, the TCP and UDP
  2160	      protocols provide the notion of a "port", which identifies the
  2161	      endpoint (usually a network server) of a communications path.  In
  2162	      some instances, it may be desirable to deny access to a specific
  2163	      TCP or UDP port, or even to certain hosts and networks altogether.
  2164	
  2165	      3.9.5.1  Gateway Routing Tables
  2166	
  2167	         One of the simplest approaches to preventing unwanted network
  2168	         connections is to simply remove certain networks from a
  2169	         gateway's routing tables.  This makes it "impossible" for a
  2170	         host to send packets to these networks.  (Most protocols
  2171	         require bidirectional packet flow even for unidirectional data
  2172	         flow, thus breaking one side of the route is usually
  2173	         sufficient.)
  2174	
  2175	         This approach is commonly taken in "firewall" systems by
  2176	         preventing the firewall from advertising local routes to the
  2177	
  2178	
  2179	
  2180	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 39]
  2181	
  2182	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  2183	
  2184	
  2185	         outside world.  The approach is deficient in that it often
  2186	         prevents "too much" (e.g., in order to prevent access to one
  2187	         system on the network, access to all systems on the network is
  2188	         disabled).
  2189	
  2190	      3.9.5.2  Router Packet Filtering
  2191	
  2192	         Many commercially available gateway systems (more correctly
  2193	         called routers) provide the ability to filter packets based not
  2194	         only on sources or destinations, but also on source-destination
  2195	         combinations.  This mechanism can be used to deny access to a
  2196	         specific host, network, or subnet from any other host, network,
  2197	         or subnet.
  2198	
  2199	         Gateway systems from some vendors (e.g., cisco Systems) support
  2200	         an even more complex scheme, allowing finer control over source
  2201	         and destination addresses.  Via the use of address masks, one
  2202	         can deny access to all but one host on a particular network.
  2203	         The cisco Systems also allow packet screening based on IP
  2204	         protocol type and TCP or UDP port numbers [14].
  2205	
  2206	         This can also be circumvented by "source routing" packets
  2207	         destined for the "secret" network.  Source routed packets may
  2208	         be filtered out by gateways, but this may restrict other
  2209	         legitimate activities, such as diagnosing routing problems.
  2210	
  2211	   3.9.6  Authentication Systems
  2212	
  2213	      Authentication refers to the process of proving a claimed identity
  2214	      to the satisfaction of some permission-granting authority.
  2215	      Authentication systems are hardware, software, or procedural
  2216	      mechanisms that enable a user to obtain access to computing
  2217	      resources.  At the simplest level, the system administrator who
  2218	      adds new user accounts to the system is part of the system
  2219	      authentication mechanism.  At the other end of the spectrum,
  2220	      fingerprint readers or retinal scanners provide a very high-tech
  2221	      solution to establishing a potential user's identity.  Without
  2222	      establishing and proving a user's identity prior to establishing a
  2223	      session, your site's computers are vulnerable to any sort of
  2224	      attack.
  2225	
  2226	      Typically, a user authenticates himself or herself to the system
  2227	      by entering a password in response to a prompt.
  2228	      Challenge/Response mechanisms improve upon passwords by prompting
  2229	      the user for some piece of information shared by both the computer
  2230	      and the user (such as mother's maiden name, etc.).
  2231	
  2232	
  2233	
  2234	
  2235	
  2236	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 40]
  2237	
  2238	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  2239	
  2240	
  2241	      3.9.6.1  Kerberos
  2242	
  2243	         Kerberos, named after the dog who in mythology is said to stand
  2244	         at the gates of Hades, is a collection of software used in a
  2245	         large network to establish a user's claimed identity.
  2246	         Developed at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT),
  2247	         it uses a combination of encryption and distributed databases
  2248	         so that a user at a campus facility can login and start a
  2249	         session from any computer located on the campus.  This has
  2250	         clear advantages in certain environments where there are a
  2251	         large number of potential users who may establish a connection
  2252	         from any one of a large number of workstations.  Some vendors
  2253	         are now incorporating Kerberos into their systems.
  2254	
  2255	         It should be noted that while Kerberos makes several advances
  2256	         in the area of authentication, some security weaknesses in the
  2257	         protocol still remain [15].
  2258	
  2259	      3.9.6.2  Smart Cards
  2260	
  2261	         Several systems use "smart cards" (a small calculator-like
  2262	         device) to help authenticate users.  These systems depend on
  2263	         the user having an object in their possession.  One such system
  2264	         involves a new password procedure that require a user to enter
  2265	         a value obtained from a "smart card" when asked for a password
  2266	         by the computer.  Typically, the host machine will give the
  2267	         user some piece of information that is entered into the
  2268	         keyboard of the smart card.  The smart card will display a
  2269	         response which must then be entered into the computer before
  2270	         the session will be established.  Another such system involves
  2271	         a smart card which displays a number which changes over time,
  2272	         but which is synchronized with the authentication software on
  2273	         the computer.
  2274	
  2275	         This is a better way of dealing with authentication than with
  2276	         the traditional password approach.  On the other hand, some say
  2277	         it's inconvenient to carry the smart card.  Start-up costs are
  2278	         likely to be high as well.
  2279	
  2280	   3.9.7  Books, Lists, and Informational Sources
  2281	
  2282	      There are many good sources for information regarding computer
  2283	      security.  The annotated bibliography at the end of this document
  2284	      can provide you with a good start.  In addition, information can
  2285	      be obtained from a variety of other sources, some of which are
  2286	      described in this section.
  2287	
  2288	
  2289	
  2290	
  2291	
  2292	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 41]
  2293	
  2294	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
