  2297	      3.9.7.1  Security Mailing Lists
  2298	
  2299	         The UNIX Security mailing list exists to notify system
  2300	         administrators of security problems before they become common
  2301	         knowledge, and to provide security enhancement information.  It
  2302	         is a restricted-access list, open only to people who can be
  2303	         verified as being principal systems people at a site.  Requests
  2304	         to join the list must be sent by either the site contact listed
  2305	         in the Defense Data Network's Network Information Center's (DDN
  2306	         NIC) WHOIS database, or from the "root" account on one of the
  2307	         major site machines.  You must include the destination address
  2308	         you want on the list, an indication of whether you want to be
  2309	         on the mail reflector list or receive weekly digests, the
  2310	         electronic mail address and voice telephone number of the site
  2311	         contact if it isn't you, and the name, address, and telephone
  2312	         number of your organization.  This information should be sent
  2313	         to SECURITY-REQUEST@CPD.COM.
  2314	
  2315	         The RISKS digest is a component of the ACM Committee on
  2316	         Computers and Public Policy, moderated by Peter G. Neumann.  It
  2317	         is a discussion forum on risks to the public in computers and
  2318	         related systems, and along with discussing computer security
  2319	         and privacy issues, has discussed such subjects as the Stark
  2320	         incident, the shooting down of the Iranian airliner in the
  2321	         Persian Gulf (as it relates to the computerized weapons
  2322	         systems), problems in air and railroad traffic control systems,
  2323	         software engineering, and so on.  To join the mailing list,
  2324	         send a message to RISKS-REQUEST@CSL.SRI.COM.  This list is also
  2325	         available in the USENET newsgroup "comp.risks".
  2326	
  2327	         The VIRUS-L list is a forum for the discussion of computer
  2328	         virus experiences, protection software, and related topics.
  2329	         The list is open to the public, and is implemented as a
  2330	         moderated digest.  Most of the information is related to
  2331	         personal computers, although some of it may be applicable to
  2332	         larger systems.  To subscribe, send the line:
  2333	
  2334	            SUB VIRUS-L your full name
  2335	
  2336	         to the address LISTSERV%LEHIIBM1.BITNET@MITVMA.MIT.EDU.  This
  2337	         list is also available via the USENET newsgroup "comp.virus".
  2338	
  2339	         The Computer Underground Digest "is an open forum dedicated to
  2340	         sharing information among computerists and to the presentation
  2341	         and debate of diverse views."  While not directly a security
  2342	         list, it does contain discussions about privacy and other
  2343	         security related topics.  The list can be read on USENET as
  2344	         alt.society.cu-digest, or to join the mailing list, send mail
  2345	
  2346	
  2347	
  2348	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 42]
  2349	
  2350	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  2351	
  2352	
  2353	         to Gordon Myer (TK0JUT2%NIU.bitnet@mitvma.mit.edu).
  2354	         Submissions may be mailed to: cud@chinacat.unicom.com.
  2355	
  2356	      3.9.7.2  Networking Mailing Lists
  2357	
  2358	         The TCP-IP mailing list is intended to act as a discussion
  2359	         forum for developers and maintainers of implementations of the
  2360	         TCP/IP protocol suite.  It also discusses network-related
  2361	         security problems when they involve programs providing network
  2362	         services, such as "Sendmail".  To join the TCP-IP list, send a
  2363	         message to TCP-IP-REQUEST@NISC.SRI.COM.  This list is also
  2364	         available in the USENET newsgroup "comp.protocols.tcp-ip".
  2365	
  2366	         SUN-NETS is a discussion list for items pertaining to
  2367	         networking on Sun systems.  Much of the discussion is related
  2368	         to NFS, NIS (formally Yellow Pages), and name servers.  To
  2369	         subscribe, send a message to SUN-NETS-REQUEST@UMIACS.UMD.EDU.
  2370	
  2371	         The USENET groups misc.security and alt.security also discuss
  2372	         security issues.  misc.security is a moderated group and also
  2373	         includes discussions of physical security and locks.
  2374	         alt.security is unmoderated.
