  2707	   3.9.8  Problem Reporting Tools
  2708	
  2709	      3.9.8.1  Auditing
  2710	
  2711	         Auditing is an important tool that can be used to enhance the
  2712	         security of your installation.  Not only does it give you a
  2713	         means of identifying who has accessed your system (and may have
  2714	         done something to it) but it also gives you an indication of
  2715	         how your system is being used (or abused) by authorized users
  2716	         and attackers alike.  In addition, the audit trail
  2717	         traditionally kept by computer systems can become an invaluable
  2718	         piece of evidence should your system be penetrated.
  2719	
  2720	         3.9.8.1.1  Verify Security
  2721	
  2722	            An audit trail shows how the system is being used from day
  2723	            to day.  Depending upon how your site audit log is
  2724	            configured, your log files should show a range of access
  2725	            attempts that can show what normal system usage should look
  2726	            like.  Deviation from that normal usage could be the result
  2727	            of penetration from an outside source using an old or stale
  2728	            user account.  Observing a deviation in logins, for example,
  2729	            could be your first indication that something unusual is
  2730	            happening.
  2731	
  2732	         3.9.8.1.2  Verify Software Configurations
  2733	
  2734	            One of the ruses used by attackers to gain access to a
  2735	            system is by the insertion of a so-called Trojan Horse
  2736	            program.  A Trojan Horse program can be a program that does
  2737	
  2738	
  2739	
  2740	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 49]
  2741	
  2742	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  2743	
  2744	
  2745	            something useful, or merely something interesting.  It
  2746	            always does something unexpected, like steal passwords or
  2747	            copy files without your knowledge [25].  Imagine a Trojan
  2748	            login program that prompts for username and password in the
  2749	            usual way, but also writes that information to a special
  2750	            file that the attacker can come back and read at will.
  2751	            Imagine a Trojan Editor program that, despite the file
  2752	            permissions you have given your files, makes copies of
  2753	            everything in your directory space without you knowing about
  2754	            it.
  2755	
  2756	            This points out the need for configuration management of the
  2757	            software that runs on a system, not as it is being
  2758	            developed, but as it is in actual operation.  Techniques for
  2759	            doing this range from checking each command every time it is
  2760	            executed against some criterion (such as a cryptoseal,
  2761	            described above) or merely checking the date and time stamp
  2762	            of the executable.  Another technique might be to check each
  2763	            command in batch mode at midnight.
  2764	
  2765	      3.9.8.2  Tools
  2766	
  2767	         COPS is a security tool for system administrators that checks
  2768	         for numerous common security problems on UNIX systems [27].
  2769	         COPS is a collection of shell scripts and C programs that can
  2770	         easily be run on almost any UNIX variant.  Among other things,
  2771	         it checks the following items and sends the results to the
  2772	         system administrator:
  2773	
  2774	            - Checks "/dev/kmem" and other devices for world
  2775	              read/writability.
  2776	
  2777	            - Checks special or important files and directories for
  2778	              "bad" modes (world writable, etc.).
  2779	
  2780	            - Checks for easily-guessed passwords.
  2781	
  2782	            - Checks for duplicate user ids, invalid fields in the
  2783	              password file, etc..
  2784	
  2785	            - Checks for duplicate group ids, invalid fields in the
  2786	              group file, etc..
  2787	
  2788	            - Checks all users' home directories and their ".cshrc",
  2789	              ".login", ".profile", and ".rhosts" files for security
  2790	              problems.
  2791	
  2792	            - Checks all commands in the "/etc/rc" files and "cron"
  2793	
  2794	
  2795	
  2796	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 50]
  2797	
  2798	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  2799	
  2800	
  2801	              files for world writability.
  2802	
  2803	            - Checks for bad "root" paths, NFS file systems exported
  2804	              to the world, etc..
  2805	
  2806	            - Includes an expert system that checks to see if a given
  2807	              user (usually "root") can be compromised, given that
  2808	              certain rules are true.
  2809	
  2810	            - Checks for changes in the setuid status of programs on the
  2811	              system.
  2812	
  2813	         The COPS package is available from the "comp.sources.unix"
  2814	         archive on "ftp.uu.net", and also from the UNIX-SW repository
  2815	         on the MILNET host "wsmr-simtel20.army.mil".
  2816	
