  2928	
  2929	      3.9.9.2  Obtaining Fixes for Known Problems
  2930	
  2931	         It goes without saying that computer systems have bugs.  Even
  2932	         operating systems, upon which we depend for protection of our
  2933	         data, have bugs.  And since there are bugs, things can be
  2934	         broken, both maliciously and accidentally.  It is important
  2935	         that whenever bugs are discovered, a should fix be identified
  2936	         and implemented as soon as possible.  This should minimize any
  2937	         exposure caused by the bug in the first place.
  2938	
  2939	         A corollary to the bug problem is: from whom do I obtain the
  2940	         fixes?  Most systems have some support from the manufacturer or
  2941	         supplier.  Fixes coming from that source tend to be implemented
  2942	         quickly after receipt.  Fixes for some problems are often
  2943	         posted on the network and are left to the system administrators
  2944	         to incorporate as they can.  The problem is that one wants to
  2945	         have faith that the fix will close the hole and not introduce
  2946	         any others.  We will tend to trust that the manufacturer's
  2947	         fixes are better than those that are posted on the net.
  2948	
  2949	      3.9.9.3  Sun Customer Warning System
  2950	
  2951	         Sun Microsystems has established a Customer Warning System
  2952	         (CWS) for handling security incidents.  This is a formal
  2953	         process which includes:
  2954	
  2955	            - Having a well advertised point of contact in Sun
  2956	              for reporting security problems.
  2957	            - Pro-actively alerting customers of worms, viruses,
  2958	              or other security holes that could affect their systems.
  2959	            - Distributing the patch (or work-around) as quickly
  2960	              as possible.
  2961	
  2962	
  2963	
  2964	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 53]
  2965	
  2966	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  2967	
  2968	
  2969	         They have created an electronic mail address, SECURITY-
  2970	         ALERT@SUN.COM, which will enable customers to report security
  2971	         problems.  A voice-mail backup is available at (415) 688-9081.
  2972	         A "Security Contact" can be designated by each customer site;
  2973	         this person will be contacted by Sun in case of any new
  2974	         security problems.  For more information, contact your Sun
  2975	         representative.
  2976	
  2977	      3.9.9.4  Trusted Archive Servers
  2978	
  2979	         Several sites on the Internet maintain large repositories of
  2980	         public-domain and freely distributable software, and make this
  2981	         material available for anonymous FTP.  This section describes
  2982	         some of the larger repositories.  Note that none of these
  2983	         servers implements secure checksums or anything else
  2984	         guaranteeing the integrity of their data.  Thus, the notion of
  2985	         "trust" should be taken as a somewhat limited definition.
  2986	
  2987	         3.9.9.4.1  Sun Fixes on UUNET
  2988	
  2989	            Sun Microsystems has contracted with UUNET Communications
  2990	            Services, Inc., to make fixes for bugs in Sun software
  2991	            available via anonymous FTP.  You can access these fixes by
  2992	            using the "ftp" command to connect to the host FTP.UU.NET.
  2993	            Then change into the directory "sun-dist/security", and
  2994	            obtain a directory listing.  The file "README" contains a
  2995	            brief description of what each file in this directory
  2996	            contains, and what is required to install the fix.
  2997	
  2998	         3.9.9.4.2  Berkeley Fixes
  2999	
  3000	            The University of California at Berkeley also makes fixes
  3001	            available via anonymous FTP; these fixes pertain primarily
  3002	            to the current release of BSD UNIX (currently, release 4.3).
  3003	            However, even if you are not running their software, these
  3004	            fixes are still important, since many vendors (Sun, DEC,
  3005	            Sequent, etc.) base their software on the Berkeley releases.
  3006	
  3007	            The Berkeley fixes are available for anonymous FTP from the
  3008	            host UCBARPA.BERKELEY.EDU in the directory "4.3/ucb-fixes".
  3009	            The file "INDEX" in this directory describes what each file
  3010	            contains.  They are also available from UUNET (see section
  3011	            3.9.9.4.3).
  3012	
  3013	            Berkeley also distributes new versions of "sendmail" and
  3014	            "named" from this machine.  New versions of these commands
  3015	            are stored in the "4.3" directory, usually in the files
  3016	            "sendmail.tar.Z" and "bind.tar.Z", respectively.
  3017	
  3018	
  3019	
  3020	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 54]
  3021	
  3022	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3023	
  3024	
  3025	         3.9.9.4.3  Simtel-20 and UUNET
  3026	
  3027	            The two largest general-purpose software repositories on the
  3028	            Internet are the hosts WSMR-SIMTEL20.ARMY.MIL and
  3029	            FTP.UU.NET.
  3030	
  3031	            WSMR-SIMTEL20.ARMY.MIL is a TOPS-20 machine operated by the
