  3056	
  3057	         3.9.9.4.4  Vendors
  3058	
  3059	            Many vendors make fixes for bugs in their software available
  3060	            electronically, either via mailing lists or via anonymous
  3061	            FTP.  You should contact your vendor to find out if they
  3062	            offer this service, and if so, how to access it.  Some
  3063	            vendors that offer these services include Sun Microsystems
  3064	            (see above), Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC), the
  3065	            University of California at Berkeley (see above), and Apple
  3066	            Computer [5, CURRY].
  3067	
  3068	
  3069	
  3070	
  3071	
  3072	
  3073	
  3074	
  3075	
  3076	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 55]
  3077	
  3078	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3079	
  3080	
  3081	4.  Types of Security Procedures
  3082	
  3083	4.1  System Security Audits
  3084	
  3085	   Most businesses undergo some sort of annual financial auditing as a
  3086	   regular part of their business life.  Security audits are an
  3087	   important part of running any computing environment.  Part of the
  3088	   security audit should be a review of any policies that concern system
  3089	   security, as well as the mechanisms that are put in place to enforce
  3090	   them.
  3091	
  3092	   4.1.1   Organize Scheduled Drills
  3093	
  3094	      Although not something that would be done each day or week,
  3095	      scheduled drills may be conducted to determine if the procedures
  3096	      defined are adequate for the threat to be countered.  If your
  3097	      major threat is one of natural disaster, then a drill would be
  3098	      conducted to verify your backup and recovery mechanisms.  On the
  3099	      other hand, if your greatest threat is from external intruders
  3100	      attempting to penetrate your system, a drill might be conducted to
  3101	      actually try a penetration to observe the effect of the policies.
  3102	
  3103	      Drills are a valuable way to test that your policies and
  3104	      procedures are effective.  On the other hand, drills can be time-
  3105	      consuming and disruptive to normal operations.  It is important to
  3106	      weigh the benefits of the drills against the possible time loss
  3107	      which may be associated with them.
  3108	
  3109	   4.1.2  Test Procedures
  3110	
  3111	      If the choice is made to not to use scheduled drills to examine
  3112	      your entire security procedure at one time, it is important to
  3113	      test individual procedures frequently.  Examine your backup
  3114	      procedure to make sure you can recover data from the tapes.  Check
  3115	      log files to be sure that information which is supposed to be
  3116	      logged to them is being logged to them, etc..
  3117	
  3118	      When a security audit is mandated, great care should be used in
  3119	      devising tests of the security policy.  It is important to clearly
  3120	      identify what is being tested, how the test will be conducted, and
  3121	      results expected from the test.  This should all be documented and
  3122	      included in or as an adjunct to the security policy document
  3123	      itself.
  3124	
  3125	      It is important to test all aspects of the security policy, both
  3126	      procedural and automated, with a particular emphasis on the
  3127	      automated mechanisms used to enforce the policy.  Tests should be
  3128	      defined to ensure a comprehensive examination of policy features,
  3129	
  3130	
  3131	
  3132	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 56]
  3133	
  3134	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3135	
  3136	
  3137	      that is, if a test is defined to examine the user logon process,
  3138	      it should be explicitly stated that both valid and invalid user
  3139	      names and passwords will be used to demonstrate proper operation
  3140	      of the logon program.
  3141	
  3142	      Keep in mind that there is a limit to the reasonableness of tests.
  3143	      The purpose of testing is to ensure confidence that the security
  3144	      policy is being correctly enforced, and not to "prove" the
  3145	      absoluteness of the system or policy.  The goal should be to
  3146	      obtain some assurance that the reasonable and credible controls
  3147	      imposed by your security policy are adequate.
  3148	
  3149	4.2  Account Management Procedures
  3150	
  3151	   Procedures to manage accounts are important in preventing
  3152	   unauthorized access to your system.  It is necessary to decide
  3153	   several things: Who may have an account on the system?  How long may
  3154	   someone have an account without renewing his or her request?  How do
  3155	   old accounts get removed from the system?  The answers to all these
  3156	   questions should be explicitly set out in the policy.
  3157	
  3158	   In addition to deciding who may use a system, it may be important to
  3159	   determine what each user may use the system for (is personal use
  3160	   allowed, for example).  If you are connected to an outside network,
  3161	   your site or the network management may have rules about what the
  3162	   network may be used for.  Therefore, it is important for any security
  3163	   policy to define an adequate account management procedure for both
  3164	   administrators and users.  Typically, the system administrator would
  3165	   be responsible for creating and deleting user accounts and generally
  3166	   maintaining overall control of system use.  To some degree, account
  3167	   management is also the responsibility of each system user in the
  3168	   sense that the user should observe any system messages and events
  3169	   that may be indicative of a policy violation.  For example, a message
  3170	   at logon that indicates the date and time of the last logon should be
  3171	   reported by the user if it indicates an unreasonable time of last
  3172	   logon.
  3173	
  3174	4.3  Password Management Procedures
  3175	
  3176	   A policy on password management may be important if your site wishes
  3177	   to enforce secure passwords.  These procedures may range from asking
  3178	   or forcing users to change their passwords occasionally to actively
  3179	   attempting to break users' passwords and then informing the user of
  3180	   how easy it was to do.  Another part of password management policy
  3181	   covers who may distribute passwords - can users give their passwords
  3182	   to other users?
  3183	
  3184	   Section 2.3 discusses some of the policy issues that need to be
  3185	
  3186	
  3187	
  3188	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 57]
  3189	
  3190	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3191	
  3192	
  3193	   decided for proper password management.  Regardless of the policies,
  3194	   password management procedures need to be carefully setup to avoid
  3195	   disclosing passwords.  The choice of initial passwords for accounts
  3196	   is critical.  In some cases, users may never login to activate an
  3197	   account; thus, the choice of the initial password should not be
  3198	   easily guessed.  Default passwords should never be assigned to
  3199	   accounts: always create new passwords for each user.  If there are
  3200	   any printed lists of passwords, these should be kept off-line in
  3201	   secure locations; better yet, don't list passwords.
  3202	
  3203	   4.3.1  Password Selection
  3204	
  3205	      Perhaps the most vulnerable part of any computer system is the
  3206	      account password.  Any computer system, no matter how secure it is
  3207	      from network or dial-up attack, Trojan horse programs, and so on,
  3208	      can be fully exploited by an intruder if he or she can gain access
  3209	      via a poorly chosen password.  It is important to define a good
  3210	      set of rules for password selection, and distribute these rules to
  3211	      all users.  If possible, the software which sets user passwords
  3212	      should be modified to enforce as many of the rules as possible.
  3213	
  3214	      A sample set of guidelines for password selection is shown below:
  3215	
  3216	         - DON'T use your login name in any form (as-is,
  3217	           reversed, capitalized, doubled, etc.).
  3218	
  3219	         - DON'T use your first, middle, or last name in any form.
  3220	
  3221	         - DON'T use your spouse's or child's name.
  3222	
  3223	         - DON'T use other information easily obtained about you.
  3224	           This includes license plate numbers, telephone numbers,
  3225	           social security numbers, the make of your automobile,
  3226	           the name of the street you live on, etc..
  3227	
  3228	         - DON'T use a password of all digits, or all the same
  3229	           letter.
  3230	
  3231	         - DON'T use a word contained in English or foreign
  3232	           language dictionaries, spelling lists, or other
  3233	           lists of words.
  3234	
  3235	         - DON'T use a password shorter than six characters.
  3236	
  3237	         - DO use a password with mixed-case alphabetics.
  3238	
  3239	         - DO use a password with non-alphabetic characters (digits
  3240	           or punctuation).
  3241	
  3242	
  3243	
  3244	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 58]
  3245	
  3246	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3247	
  3248	
  3249	         - DO use a password that is easy to remember, so you don't
  3250	           have to write it down.
  3251	
  3252	         - DO use a password that you can type quickly, without
  3253	           having to look at the keyboard.
  3254	
  3255	      Methods of selecting a password which adheres to these guidelines
  3256	      include:
  3257	
  3258	         - Choose a line or two from a song or poem, and use the
  3259	           first letter of each word.
  3260	
  3261	         - Alternate between one consonant and one or two vowels, up
  3262	           to seven or eight characters.  This provides nonsense
  3263	           words which are usually pronounceable, and thus easily
  3264	           remembered.
  3265	
  3266	         - Choose two short words and concatenate them together with
  3267	           a punctuation character between them.
  3268	
  3269	      Users should also be told to change their password periodically,
  3270	      usually every three to six months.  This makes sure that an
  3271	      intruder who has guessed a password will eventually lose access,
  3272	      as well as invalidating any list of passwords he/she may have
  3273	      obtained.  Many systems enable the system administrator to force
  3274	      users to change their passwords after an expiration period; this
  3275	      software should be enabled if your system supports it [5, CURRY].
  3276	
  3277	      Some systems provide software which forces users to change their
  3278	      passwords on a regular basis.  Many of these systems also include
  3279	      password generators which provide the user with a set of passwords
  3280	      to choose from.  The user is not permitted to make up his or her
  3281	      own password.  There are arguments both for and against systems
  3282	      such as these.  On the one hand, by using generated passwords,
  3283	      users are prevented from selecting insecure passwords.  On the
  3284	      other hand, unless the generator is good at making up easy to
  3285	      remember passwords, users will begin writing them down in order to
  3286	      remember them.
  3287	
  3288	   4.3.2  Procedures for Changing Passwords
  3289	
  3290	      How password changes are handled is important to keeping passwords
  3291	      secure.  Ideally, users should be able to change their own
  3292	      passwords on-line.  (Note that password changing programs are a
  3293	      favorite target of intruders.  See section 4.4 on configuration
  3294	      management for further information.)
  3295	
  3296	      However, there are exception cases which must be handled
  3297	
  3298	
  3299	
  3300	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 59]
  3301	
  3302	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3303	
  3304	
  3305	      carefully.  Users may forget passwords and not be able to get onto
  3306	      the system.  The standard procedure is to assign the user a new
  3307	      password.  Care should be taken to make sure that the real person
  3308	      is requesting the change and gets the new password.  One common
  3309	      trick used by intruders is to call or message to a system
  3310	      administrator and request a new password. Some external form of
  3311	      verification should be used before the password is assigned.  At
  3312	      some sites, users are required to show up in person with ID.
  3313	
  3314	      There may also be times when many passwords need to be changed.
  3315	      If a system is compromised by an intruder, the intruder may be
  3316	      able to steal a password file and take it off the system.  Under
  3317	      these circumstances, one course of action is to change all
  3318	      passwords on the system.  Your site should have procedures for how
  3319	      this can be done quickly and efficiently.  What course you choose
  3320	      may depend on the urgency of the problem.  In the case of a known
  3321	      attack with damage, you may choose to forcibly disable all
  3322	      accounts and assign users new passwords before they come back onto
  3323	      the system.  In some places, users are sent a message telling them
  3324	      that they should change their passwords, perhaps within a certain
  3325	      time period.  If the password isn't changed before the time period
  3326	      expires, the account is locked.
  3327	
  3328	      Users should be aware of what the standard procedure is for
  3329	      passwords when a security event has occurred.  One well-known
  3330	      spoof reported by the Computer Emergency Response Team (CERT)
  3331	      involved messages sent to users, supposedly from local system
  3332	      administrators, requesting them to immediately change their
  3333	      password to a new value provided in the message [24].  These
  3334	      messages were not from the administrators, but from intruders
  3335	      trying to steal accounts.  Users should be warned to immediately
  3336	      report any suspicious requests such as this to site
  3337	      administrators.
  3338	
  3339	4.4  Configuration Management Procedures
  3340	
  3341	   Configuration management is generally applied to the software
  3342	   development process.  However, it is certainly applicable in a
  3343	   operational sense as well.  Consider that the since many of the
  3344	   system level programs are intended to enforce the security policy, it
  3345	   is important that these be "known" as correct.  That is, one should
  3346	   not allow system level programs (such as the operating system, etc.)
  3347	   to be changed arbitrarily.  At very least, the procedures should
  3348	   state who is authorized to make changes to systems, under what
  3349	   circumstances, and how the changes should be documented.
  3350	
  3351	   In some environments, configuration management is also desirable as
  3352	   applied to physical configuration of equipment.  Maintaining valid
  3353	
  3354	
  3355	
  3356	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 60]
  3357	
  3358	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3359	
  3360	
  3361	   and authorized hardware configuration should be given due
  3362	   consideration in your security policy.
  3363	
  3364	   4.4.1  Non-Standard Configurations
  3365	
  3366	      Occasionally, it may be beneficial to have a slightly non-standard
  3367	      configuration in order to thwart the "standard" attacks used by
  3368	      some intruders.  The non-standard parts of the configuration might
  3369	      include different password encryption algorithms, different
  3370	      configuration file locations, and rewritten or functionally
  3371	      limited system commands.
  3372	
  3373	      Non-standard configurations, however, also have their drawbacks.
  3374	      By changing the "standard" system, these modifications make
  3375	      software maintenance more difficult by requiring extra
  3376	      documentation to be written, software modification after operating
  3377	      system upgrades, and, usually, someone with special knowledge of
  3378	      the changes.
  3379	
  3380	      Because of the drawbacks of non-standard configurations, they are
  3381	      often only used in environments with a "firewall" machine (see
  3382	      section 3.9.1).  The firewall machine is modified in non-standard
  3383	      ways since it is susceptible to attack, while internal systems
  3384	      behind the firewall are left in their standard configurations.
  3385	
  3386	5.  Incident Handling
  3387	
  3388	5.1  Overview
  3389	
  3390	   This section of the document will supply some guidance to be applied
  3391	   when a computer security event is in progress on a machine, network,
  3392	   site, or multi-site environment.  The operative philosophy in the
  3393	   event of a breach of computer security, whether it be an external
  3394	   intruder attack or a disgruntled employee, is to plan for adverse
  3395	   events in advance.  There is no substitute for creating contingency
  3396	   plans for the types of events described above.
  3397	
  3398	   Traditional computer security, while quite important in the overall
  3399	   site security plan, usually falls heavily on protecting systems from
  3400	   attack, and perhaps monitoring systems to detect attacks.  Little
  3401	   attention is usually paid for how to actually handle the attack when
  3402	   it occurs.  The result is that when an attack is in progress, many
  3403	   decisions are made in haste and can be damaging to tracking down the
  3404	   source of the incident, collecting evidence to be used in prosecution
  3405	   efforts, preparing for the recovery of the system, and protecting the
  3406	   valuable data contained on the system.
  3407	
  3408	
  3409	
  3410	
  3411	
  3412	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 61]
  3413	
  3414	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3415	
  3416	
  3417	   5.1.1  Have a Plan to Follow in Case of an Incident
  3418	
  3419	      Part of handling an incident is being prepared to respond before
  3420	      the incident occurs.  This includes establishing a suitable level
  3421	      of protections, so that if the incident becomes severe, the damage
  3422	      which can occur is limited.  Protection includes preparing
  3423	      incident handling guidelines or a contingency response plan for
  3424	      your organization or site.  Having written plans eliminates much
  3425	      of the ambiguity which occurs during an incident, and will lead to
  3426	      a more appropriate and thorough set of responses.  Second, part of
  3427	      protection is preparing a method of notification, so you will know
  3428	      who to call and the relevant phone numbers.  It is important, for
  3429	      example, to conduct "dry runs," in which your computer security
  3430	      personnel, system administrators, and managers simulate handling
  3431	      an incident.
  3432	
  3433	      Learning to respond efficiently to an incident is important for
  3434	      numerous reasons.  The most important benefit is directly to human
  3435	      beings--preventing loss of human life.  Some computing systems are
  3436	      life critical systems, systems on which human life depends (e.g.,
  3437	      by controlling some aspect of life-support in a hospital or
  3438	      assisting air traffic controllers).
  3439	
  3440	      An important but often overlooked benefit is an economic one.
  3441	      Having both technical and managerial personnel respond to an
  3442	      incident requires considerable resources, resources which could be
  3443	      utilized more profitably if an incident did not require their
  3444	      services.  If these personnel are trained to handle an incident
  3445	      efficiently, less of their time is required to deal with that
  3446	      incident.
  3447	
  3448	      A third benefit is protecting classified, sensitive, or
  3449	      proprietary information.  One of the major dangers of a computer
  3450	      security incident is that information may be irrecoverable.
  3451	      Efficient incident handling minimizes this danger.  When
  3452	      classified information is involved, other government regulations
  3453	      may apply and must be integrated into any plan for incident
  3454	      handling.
  3455	
  3456	      A fourth benefit is related to public relations.  News about
  3457	      computer security incidents tends to be damaging to an
  3458	      organization's stature among current or potential clients.
  3459	      Efficient incident handling minimizes the potential for negative
  3460	      exposure.
  3461	
  3462	      A final benefit of efficient incident handling is related to legal
  3463	      issues.  It is possible that in the near future organizations may
  3464	      be sued because one of their nodes was used to launch a network
  3465	
  3466	
  3467	
  3468	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 62]
  3469	
  3470	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3471	
  3472	
  3473	      attack.  In a similar vein, people who develop patches or
  3474	      workarounds may be sued if the patches or workarounds are
  3475	      ineffective, resulting in damage to systems, or if the patches or
  3476	      workarounds themselves damage systems.  Knowing about operating
  3477	      system vulnerabilities and patterns of attacks and then taking
  3478	      appropriate measures is critical to circumventing possible legal
  3479	      problems.
  3480	
  3481	   5.1.2  Order of Discussion in this Session Suggests an Order for
  3482	          a Plan
  3483	
  3484	      This chapter is arranged such that a list may be generated from
  3485	      the Table of Contents to provide a starting point for creating a
  3486	      policy for handling ongoing incidents.  The main points to be
  3487	      included in a policy for handling incidents are:
  3488	
  3489	         o Overview (what are the goals and objectives in handling the
  3490	           incident).
  3491	         o Evaluation (how serious is the incident).
  3492	         o Notification (who should be notified about the incident).
  3493	         o Response (what should the response to the incident be).
  3494	         o Legal/Investigative (what are the legal and prosecutorial
  3495	           implications of the incident).
  3496	         o Documentation Logs (what records should be kept from before,
  3497	           during, and after the incident).
  3498	
  3499	      Each of these points is important in an overall plan for handling
  3500	      incidents.  The remainder of this chapter will detail the issues
  3501	      involved in each of these topics, and provide some guidance as to
  3502	      what should be included in a site policy for handling incidents.
  3503	
  3504	      5.1.3  Possible Goals and Incentives for Efficient Incident
  3505	             Handling
  3506	
  3507	      As in any set of pre-planned procedures, attention must be placed
  3508	      on a set of goals to be obtained in handling an incident.  These
  3509	      goals will be placed in order of importance depending on the site,
  3510	      but one such set of goals might be:
  3511	
  3512	         Assure integrity of (life) critical systems.
  3513	         Maintain and restore data.
  3514	         Maintain and restore service.
  3515	         Figure out how it happened.
  3516	         Avoid escalation and further incidents.
  3517	         Avoid negative publicity.
  3518	         Find out who did it.
  3519	         Punish the attackers.
  3520	
  3521	
  3522	
  3523	
  3524	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 63]
  3525	
  3526	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3527	
  3528	
  3529	      It is important to prioritize actions to be taken during an
  3530	      incident well in advance of the time an incident occurs.
  3531	      Sometimes an incident may be so complex that it is impossible to
  3532	      do everything at once to respond to it; priorities are essential.
  3533	      Although priorities will vary from institution-to-institution, the
  3534	      following suggested priorities serve as a starting point for
  3535	      defining an organization's response:
  3536	
  3537	         o Priority one -- protect human life and people's
  3538	           safety; human life always has precedence over all
  3539	           other considerations.
  3540	
  3541	         o Priority two -- protect classified and/or sensitive
  3542	           data (as regulated by your site or by government
  3543	           regulations).
  3544	
  3545	         o Priority three -- protect other data, including
  3546	           proprietary, scientific, managerial and other data,
  3547	           because loss of data is costly in terms of resources.
  3548	
  3549	         o Priority four -- prevent damage to systems (e.g., loss
  3550	           or alteration of system files, damage to disk drives,
  3551	           etc.); damage to systems can result in costly down
  3552	           time and recovery.
  3553	
  3554	         o Priority five -- minimize disruption of computing
  3555	           resources; it is better in many cases to shut a system
  3556	           down or disconnect from a network than to risk damage
  3557	           to data or systems.
  3558	
  3559	      An important implication for defining priorities is that once
  3560	      human life and national security considerations have been
  3561	      addressed, it is generally more important to save data than system
  3562	      software and hardware.  Although it is undesirable to have any
  3563	      damage or loss during an incident, systems can be replaced; the
  3564	      loss or compromise of data (especially classified data), however,
  3565	      is usually not an acceptable outcome under any circumstances.
  3566	
  3567	      Part of handling an incident is being prepared to respond before
  3568	      the incident occurs.  This includes establishing a suitable level
  3569	      of protections so that if the incident becomes severe, the damage
  3570	      which can occur is limited.  Protection includes preparing
  3571	      incident handling guidelines or a contingency response plan for
  3572	      your organization or site.  Written plans eliminate much of the
  3573	      ambiguity which occurs during an incident, and will lead to a more
  3574	      appropriate and thorough set of responses.  Second, part of
  3575	      protection is preparing a method of notification so you will know
  3576	      who to call and how to contact them.  For example, every member of
  3577	
  3578	
  3579	
  3580	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 64]
  3581	
  3582	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3583	
  3584	
  3585	      the Department of Energy's CIAC Team carries a card with every
  3586	      other team member's work and home phone numbers, as well as pager
  3587	      numbers.  Third, your organization or site should establish backup
  3588	      procedures for every machine and system.  Having backups
  3589	      eliminates much of the threat of even a severe incident, since
  3590	      backups preclude serious data loss.  Fourth, you should set up
  3591	      secure systems.  This involves eliminating vulnerabilities,
  3592	      establishing an effective password policy, and other procedures,
  3593	      all of which will be explained later in this document.  Finally,
  3594	      conducting training activities is part of protection.  It is
  3595	      important, for example, to conduct "dry runs," in which your
  3596	      computer security personnel, system administrators, and managers
  3597	      simulate handling an incident.
  3598	
  3599	   5.1.4  Local Policies and Regulations Providing Guidance
  3600	
  3601	      Any plan for responding to security incidents should be guided by
  3602	      local policies and regulations.  Government and private sites that
  3603	      deal with classified material have specific rules that they must
  3604	      follow.
  3605	
  3606	      The policies your site makes about how it responds to incidents
  3607	      (as discussed in sections 2.4 and 2.5) will shape your response.
  3608	      For example, it may make little sense to create mechanisms to
  3609	      monitor and trace intruders if your site does not plan to take
  3610	      action against the intruders if they are caught.  Other
  3611	      organizations may have policies that affect your plans.  Telephone
  3612	      companies often release information about telephone traces only to
  3613	      law enforcement agencies.
  3614	
  3615	      Section 5.5 also notes that if any legal action is planned, there
  3616	      are specific guidelines that must be followed to make sure that
  3617	      any information collected can be used as evidence.
  3618	
  3619	5.2  Evaluation
  3620	
  3621	   5.2.1  Is It Real?
  3622	
  3623	      This stage involves determining the exact problem.  Of course
  3624	      many, if not most, signs often associated with virus infections,
  3625	      system intrusions, etc., are simply anomalies such as hardware
  3626	      failures.  To assist in identifying whether there really is an
  3627	      incident, it is usually helpful to obtain and use any detection
  3628	      software which may be available.  For example, widely available
  3629	      software packages can greatly assist someone who thinks there may
  3630	      be a virus in a Macintosh computer.  Audit information is also
  3631	      extremely useful, especially in determining whether there is a
  3632	      network attack.  It is extremely important to obtain a system
  3633	
  3634	
  3635	
  3636	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 65]
  3637	
  3638	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3639	
  3640	
  3641	      snapshot as soon as one suspects that something is wrong.  Many
  3642	      incidents cause a dynamic chain of events to occur, and an initial
  3643	      system snapshot may do more good in identifying the problem and
  3644	      any source of attack than most other actions which can be taken at
  3645	      this stage.  Finally, it is important to start a log book.
  3646	      Recording system events, telephone conversations, time stamps,
  3647	      etc., can lead to a more rapid and systematic identification of
  3648	      the problem, and is the basis for subsequent stages of incident
  3649	      handling.
  3650	
  3651	      There are certain indications or "symptoms" of an incident which
  3652	      deserve special attention:
  3653	
  3654	         o System crashes.
  3655	         o New user accounts (e.g., the account RUMPLESTILTSKIN
  3656	           has unexplainedly been created), or high activity on
  3657	           an account that has had virtually no activity for
  3658	           months.
  3659	         o New files (usually with novel or strange file names,
  3660	           such as data.xx or k).
  3661	         o Accounting discrepancies (e.g., in a UNIX system you
  3662	           might notice that the accounting file called
  3663	           /usr/admin/lastlog has shrunk, something that should
  3664	           make you very suspicious that there may be an
  3665	           intruder).
  3666	         o Changes in file lengths or dates (e.g., a user should
  3667	           be suspicious if he/she observes that the .EXE files in
  3668	           an MS DOS computer have unexplainedly grown
  3669	           by over 1800 bytes).
  3670	         o Attempts to write to system (e.g., a system manager
  3671	           notices that a privileged user in a VMS system is
  3672	           attempting to alter RIGHTSLIST.DAT).
  3673	         o Data modification or deletion (e.g., files start to
  3674	           disappear).
  3675	         o Denial of service (e.g., a system manager and all
  3676	           other users become locked out of a UNIX system, which
  3677	           has been changed to single user mode).
  3678	         o Unexplained, poor system performance (e.g., system
  3679	           response time becomes unusually slow).
  3680	         o Anomalies (e.g., "GOTCHA" is displayed on a display
  3681	           terminal or there are frequent unexplained "beeps").
  3682	         o Suspicious probes (e.g., there are numerous
  3683	           unsuccessful login attempts from another node).
  3684	         o Suspicious browsing (e.g., someone becomes a root user
  3685	           on a UNIX system and accesses file after file in one
  3686	           user's account, then another's).
  3687	
  3688	      None of these indications is absolute "proof" that an incident is
  3689	
  3690	
  3691	
  3692	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 66]
  3693	
  3694	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3695	
  3696	
  3697	      occurring, nor are all of these indications normally observed when
  3698	      an incident occurs.  If you observe any of these indications,
  3699	      however, it is important to suspect that an incident might be
  3700	      occurring, and act accordingly.  There is no formula for
  3701	      determining with 100 percent accuracy that an incident is
  3702	      occurring (possible exception: when a virus detection package
  3703	      indicates that your machine has the nVIR virus and you confirm
  3704	      this by examining contents of the nVIR resource in your Macintosh
  3705	      computer, you can be very certain that your machine is infected).
  3706	      It is best at this point to collaborate with other technical and
  3707	      computer security personnel to make a decision as a group about
  3708	      whether an incident is occurring.
  3709	
  3710	   5.2.2  Scope
  3711	
  3712	      Along with the identification of the incident is the evaluation of
  3713	      the scope and impact of the problem.  It is important to correctly
  3714	      identify the boundaries of the incident in order to effectively
  3715	      deal with it.  In addition, the impact of an incident will
  3716	      determine its priority in allocating resources to deal with the
  3717	      event.  Without an indication of the scope and impact of the
  3718	      event, it is difficult to determine a correct response.
  3719	
  3720	      In order to identify the scope and impact, a set of criteria
  3721	      should be defined which is appropriate to the site and to the type
  3722	      of connections available.  Some of the issues are:
  3723	
  3724	         o Is this a multi-site incident?
  3725	         o Are many computers at your site effected by this
  3726	           incident?
  3727	         o Is sensitive information involved?
  3728	         o What is the entry point of the incident (network,
  3729	           phone line, local terminal, etc.)?
  3730	         o Is the press involved?
  3731	         o What is the potential damage of the incident?
  3732	         o What is the estimated time to close out the incident?
  3733	         o What resources could be required
  3734	           to handle the incident?
  3735	
  3736	5.3  Possible Types of Notification
  3737	
  3738	   When you have confirmed that an incident is occurring, the
  3739	   appropriate personnel must be notified.  Who and how this
  3740	   notification is achieved is very important in keeping the event under
  3741	   control both from a technical and emotional standpoint.
  3742	
  3743	
  3744	
  3745	
  3746	
  3747	
  3748	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 67]
  3749	
  3750	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3751	
  3752	
  3753	   5.3.1  Explicit
  3754	
  3755	      First of all, any notification to either local or off-site
  3756	      personnel must be explicit.  This requires that any statement (be
  3757	      it an electronic mail message, phone call, or fax) provides
  3758	      information about the incident that is clear, concise, and fully
  3759	      qualified.  When you are notifying others that will help you to
  3760	      handle an event, a "smoke screen" will only divide the effort and
  3761	      create confusion.  If a division of labor is suggested, it is
  3762	      helpful to provide information to each section about what is being
  3763	      accomplished in other efforts.  This will not only reduce
  3764	      duplication of effort, but allow people working on parts of the
  3765	      problem to know where to obtain other information that would help
  3766	      them resolve a part of the incident.
  3767	
  3768	   5.3.2  Factual
  3769	
  3770	      Another important consideration when communicating about the
  3771	      incident is to be factual.  Attempting to hide aspects of the
  3772	      incident by providing false or incomplete information may not only
  3773	      prevent a successful resolution to the incident, but may even
  3774	      worsen the situation.  This is especially true when the press is
  3775	      involved.  When an incident severe enough to gain press attention
  3776	      is ongoing, it is likely that any false information you provide
  3777	      will not be substantiated by other sources.  This will reflect
  3778	      badly on the site and may create enough ill-will between the site
  3779	      and the press to damage the site's public relations.
  3780	
  3781	   5.3.3  Choice of Language
  3782	
  3783	      The choice of language used when notifying people about the
  3784	      incident can have a profound effect on the way that information is
  3785	      received.  When you use emotional or inflammatory terms, you raise
  3786	      the expectations of damage and negative outcomes of the incident.
  3787	      It is important to remain calm both in written and spoken
  3788	      notifications.
  3789	
  3790	      Another issue associated with the choice of language is the
  3791	      notification to non-technical or off-site personnel.  It is
  3792	      important to accurately describe the incident without undue alarm
  3793	      or confusing messages.  While it is more difficult to describe the
  3794	      incident to a non-technical audience, it is often more important.
  3795	      A non-technical description may be required for upper-level
  3796	      management, the press, or law enforcement liaisons.  The
  3797	      importance of these notifications cannot be underestimated and may
  3798	      make the difference between handling the incident properly and
  3799	      escalating to some higher level of damage.
  3800	
  3801	
  3802	
  3803	
  3804	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 68]
  3805	
  3806	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3807	
  3808	
  3809	   5.3.4  Notification of Individuals
  3810	
  3811	         o Point of Contact (POC) people (Technical, Administrative,
  3812	           Response Teams, Investigative, Legal, Vendors, Service
  3813	           providers), and which POCs are visible to whom.
  3814	         o Wider community (users).
  3815	         o Other sites that might be affected.
  3816	
  3817	      Finally, there is the question of who should be notified during
  3818	      and after the incident.  There are several classes of individuals
  3819	      that need to be considered for notification.  These are the
  3820	      technical personnel, administration, appropriate response teams
  3821	      (such as CERT or CIAC), law enforcement, vendors, and other
  3822	      service providers.  These issues are important for the central
  3823	      point of contact, since that is the person responsible for the
  3824	      actual notification of others (see section 5.3.6 for further
  3825	      information).  A list of people in each of these categories is an
  3826	      important time saver for the POC during an incident.  It is much
  3827	      more difficult to find an appropriate person during an incident
  3828	      when many urgent events are ongoing.
  3829	
  3830	      In addition to the people responsible for handling part of the
  3831	      incident, there may be other sites affected by the incident (or
  3832	      perhaps simply at risk from the incident).  A wider community of
  3833	      users may also benefit from knowledge of the incident.  Often, a
  3834	      report of the incident once it is closed out is appropriate for
  3835	      publication to the wider user community.
  3836	
  3837	   5.3.5  Public Relations - Press Releases
  3838	
  3839	      One of the most important issues to consider is when, who, and how
  3840	      much to release to the general public through the press.  There
  3841	      are many issues to consider when deciding this particular issue.
  3842	      First and foremost, if a public relations office exists for the
  3843	      site, it is important to use this office as liaison to the press.
  3844	      The public relations office is trained in the type and wording of
  3845	      information released, and will help to assure that the image of
  3846	      the site is protected during and after the incident (if possible).
  3847	      A public relations office has the advantage that you can
  3848	      communicate candidly with them, and provide a buffer between the
  3849	      constant press attention and the need of the POC to maintain
  3850	      control over the incident.
  3851	
  3852	      If a public relations office is not available, the information
  3853	      released to the press must be carefully considered.  If the
  3854	      information is sensitive, it may be advantageous to provide only
  3855	      minimal or overview information to the press.  It is quite
  3856	      possible that any information provided to the press will be
  3857	
  3858	
  3859	
  3860	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 69]
  3861	
  3862	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3863	
  3864	
  3865	      quickly reviewed by the perpetrator of the incident.  As a
  3866	      contrast to this consideration, it was discussed above that
  3867	      misleading the press can often backfire and cause more damage than
  3868	      releasing sensitive information.
  3869	
  3870	      While it is difficult to determine in advance what level of detail
  3871	      to provide to the press, some guidelines to keep in mind are:
  3872	
  3873	         o Keep the technical level of detail low.  Detailed
  3874	           information about the incident may provide enough
  3875	           information for copy-cat events or even damage the
  3876	           site's ability to prosecute once the event is over.
  3877	         o Keep the speculation out of press statements.
  3878	           Speculation of who is causing the incident or the
  3879	           motives are very likely to be in error and may cause
  3880	           an inflamed view of the incident.
  3881	         o Work with law enforcement professionals to assure that
  3882	           evidence is protected.  If prosecution is involved,
  3883	           assure that the evidence collected is not divulged to
  3884	           the press.
  3885	         o Try not to be forced into a press interview before you are
  3886	           prepared.  The popular press is famous for the "2am"
  3887	           interview, where the hope is to catch the interviewee off
  3888	           guard and obtain information otherwise not available.
  3889	         o Do not allow the press attention to detract from the
  3890	           handling of the event.  Always remember that the successful
  3891	           closure of an incident is of primary importance.
  3892	
  3893	   5.3.6  Who Needs to Get Involved?
  3894	
  3895	      There now exists a number of incident response teams (IRTs) such
  3896	      as the CERT and the CIAC. (See sections 3.9.7.3.1 and 3.9.7.3.4.)
  3897	      Teams exists for many major government agencies and large
  3898	      corporations.  If such a team is available for your site, the
  3899	      notification of this team should be of primary importance during
  3900	      the early stages of an incident.  These teams are responsible for
  3901	      coordinating computer security incidents over a range of sites and
  3902	      larger entities.  Even if the incident is believed to be contained
  3903	      to a single site, it is possible that the information available
  3904	      through a response team could help in closing out the incident.
  3905	
  3906	      In setting up a site policy for incident handling, it may be
  3907	      desirable to create an incident handling team (IHT), much like
  3908	      those teams that already exist, that will be responsible for
  3909	      handling computer security incidents for the site (or
  3910	      organization).  If such a team is created, it is essential that
  3911	      communication lines be opened between this team and other IHTs.
  3912	      Once an incident is under way, it is difficult to open a trusted
  3913	
  3914	
  3915	
  3916	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 70]
  3917	
  3918	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3919	
  3920	
  3921	      dialogue between other IHTs if none has existed before.
  3922	
  3923	5.4  Response
  3924	
  3925	   A major topic still untouched here is how to actually respond to an
  3926	   event.  The response to an event will fall into the general
  3927	   categories of containment, eradication, recovery, and follow-up.
  3928	
  3929	   Containment
  3930	
  3931	      The purpose of containment is to limit the extent of an attack.
  3932	      For example, it is important to limit the spread of a worm attack
  3933	      on a network as quickly as possible.  An essential part of
  3934	      containment is decision making (i.e., determining whether to shut
  3935	      a system down, to disconnect from a network, to monitor system or
  3936	      network activity, to set traps, to disable functions such as
  3937	      remote file transfer on a UNIX system, etc.).  Sometimes this
  3938	      decision is trivial; shut the system down if the system is
  3939	      classified or sensitive, or if proprietary information is at risk!
  3940	      In other cases, it is worthwhile to risk having some damage to the
  3941	      system if keeping the system up might enable you to identify an
  3942	      intruder.
  3943	
  3944	      The third stage, containment, should involve carrying out
  3945	      predetermined procedures.  Your organization or site should, for
  3946	      example, define acceptable risks in dealing with an incident, and
  3947	      should prescribe specific actions and strategies accordingly.
  3948	      Finally, notification of cognizant authorities should occur during
  3949	      this stage.
  3950	
  3951	   Eradication
  3952	
  3953	      Once an incident has been detected, it is important to first think
  3954	      about containing the incident.  Once the incident has been
  3955	      contained, it is now time to eradicate the cause.  Software may be
  3956	      available to help you in this effort.  For example, eradication
  3957	      software is available to eliminate most viruses which infect small
  3958	      systems.  If any bogus files have been created, it is time to
  3959	      delete them at this point.  In the case of virus infections, it is
  3960	      important to clean and reformat any disks containing infected
  3961	      files.  Finally, ensure that all backups are clean.  Many systems
  3962	      infected with viruses become periodically reinfected simply
  3963	      because people do not systematically eradicate the virus from
  3964	      backups.
  3965	
  3966	   Recovery
  3967	
  3968	      Once the cause of an incident has been eradicated, the recovery
  3969	
  3970	
  3971	
  3972	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 71]
  3973	
  3974	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  3975	
  3976	
  3977	      phase defines the next stage of action.  The goal of recovery is
  3978	      to return the system to normal.  In the case of a network-based
  3979	      attack, it is important to install patches for any operating
  3980	      system vulnerability which was exploited.
  3981	
  3982	   Follow-up
  3983	
  3984	      One of the most important stages of responding to incidents is
  3985	      also the most often omitted---the follow-up stage.  This stage is
  3986	      important because it helps those involved in handling the incident
  3987	      develop a set of "lessons learned" (see section 6.3) to improve
  3988	      future performance in such situations.  This stage also provides
  3989	      information which justifies an organization's computer security
  3990	      effort to management, and yields information which may be
  3991	      essential in legal proceedings.
  3992	
  3993	      The most important element of the follow-up stage is performing a
  3994	      postmortem analysis.  Exactly what happened, and at what times?
  3995	      How well did the staff involved with the incident perform?  What
  3996	      kind of information did the staff need quickly, and how could they
  3997	      have gotten that information as soon as possible?  What would the
  3998	      staff do differently next time?  A follow-up report is valuable
  3999	      because it provides a reference to be used in case of other
  4000	      similar incidents.  Creating a formal chronology of events
  4001	      (including time stamps) is also important for legal reasons.
  4002	      Similarly, it is also important to as quickly obtain a monetary
  4003	      estimate of the amount of damage the incident caused in terms of
  4004	      any loss of software and files, hardware damage, and manpower
  4005	      costs to restore altered files, reconfigure affected systems, and
  4006	      so forth.  This estimate may become the basis for subsequent
  4007	      prosecution activity by the FBI, the U.S. Attorney General's
  4008	      Office, etc..
  4009	
  4010	   5.4.1  What Will You Do?
  4011	
  4012	      o Restore control.
  4013	      o Relation to policy.
  4014	      o Which level of service is needed?
  4015	      o Monitor activity.
  4016	      o Constrain or shut down system.
  4017	
  4018	   5.4.2  Consider Designating a "Single Point of Contact"
  4019	
  4020	      When an incident is under way, a major issue is deciding who is in
  4021	      charge of coordinating the activity of the multitude of players.
  4022	      A major mistake that can be made is to have a number of "points of
  4023	      contact" (POC) that are not pulling their efforts together.  This
  4024	      will only add to the confusion of the event, and will probably
  4025	
  4026	
  4027	
  4028	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 72]
  4029	
  4030	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  4031	
  4032	
  4033	      lead to additional confusion and wasted or ineffective effort.
  4034	
  4035	      The single point of contact may or may not be the person "in
  4036	      charge" of the incident.  There are two distinct rolls to fill
  4037	      when deciding who shall be the point of contact and the person in
  4038	      charge of the incident.  The person in charge will make decisions
  4039	      as to the interpretation of policy applied to the event.  The
  4040	      responsibility for the handling of the event falls onto this
  4041	      person.  In contrast, the point of contact must coordinate the
  4042	      effort of all the parties involved with handling the event.
  4043	
  4044	      The point of contact must be a person with the technical expertise
  4045	      to successfully coordinate the effort of the system managers and
  4046	      users involved in monitoring and reacting to the attack.  Often
  4047	      the management structure of a site is such that the administrator
  4048	      of a set of resources is not a technically competent person with
  4049	      regard to handling the details of the operations of the computers,
  4050	      but is ultimately responsible for the use of these resources.
  4051	
  4052	      Another important function of the POC is to maintain contact with
  4053	      law enforcement and other external agencies (such as the CIA, DoD,
  4054	      U.S.  Army, or others) to assure that multi-agency involvement
  4055	      occurs.
  4056	
  4057	      Finally, if legal action in the form of prosecution is involved,
  4058	      the POC may be able to speak for the site in court.  The
  4059	      alternative is to have multiple witnesses that will be hard to
  4060	      coordinate in a legal sense, and will weaken any case against the
  4061	      attackers.  A single POC may also be the single person in charge
  4062	      of evidence collected, which will keep the number of people
  4063	      accounting for evidence to a minimum.  As a rule of thumb, the
  4064	      more people that touch a potential piece of evidence, the greater
  4065	      the possibility that it will be inadmissible in court.  The
  4066	      section below (Legal/Investigative) will provide more details for
  4067	      consideration on this topic.
  4068	
  4069	5.5  Legal/Investigative
  4070	
  4071	   5.5.1  Establishing Contacts with Investigative Agencies
  4072	
  4073	      It is important to establish contacts with personnel from
  4074	      investigative agencies such as the FBI and Secret Service as soon
  4075	      as possible, for several reasons.  Local law enforcement and local
  4076	      security offices or campus police organizations should also be
  4077	      informed when appropriate.  A primary reason is that once a major
  4078	      attack is in progress, there is little time to call various
  4079	      personnel in these agencies to determine exactly who the correct
  4080	      point of contact is.  Another reason is that it is important to
  4081	
  4082	
  4083	
  4084	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 73]
  4085	
  4086	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  4087	
  4088	
  4089	      cooperate with these agencies in a manner that will foster a good
  4090	      working relationship, and that will be in accordance with the
  4091	      working procedures of these agencies.  Knowing the working
  4092	      procedures in advance and the expectations of your point of
  4093	      contact is a big step in this direction.  For example, it is
  4094	      important to gather evidence that will be admissible in a court of
  4095	      law.  If you don't know in advance how to gather admissible
  4096	      evidence, your efforts to collect evidence during an incident are
  4097	      likely to be of no value to the investigative agency with which
  4098	      you deal.  A final reason for establishing contacts as soon as
  4099	      possible is that it is impossible to know the particular agency
  4100	      that will assume jurisdiction in any given incident.  Making
  4101	      contacts and finding the proper channels early will make
  4102	      responding to an incident go considerably more smoothly.
  4103	
  4104	      If your organization or site has a legal counsel, you need to
  4105	      notify this office soon after you learn that an incident is in
  4106	      progress.  At a minimum, your legal counsel needs to be involved
  4107	      to protect the legal and financial interests of your site or
  4108	      organization.  There are many legal and practical issues, a few of
  4109	      which are:
  4110	
  4111	         1. Whether your site or organization is willing to risk
  4112	            negative publicity or exposure to cooperate with legal
  4113	            prosecution efforts.
  4114	
  4115	         2. Downstream liability--if you leave a compromised system
  4116	            as is so it can be monitored and another computer is damaged
  4117	            because the attack originated from your system, your site or
  4118	            organization may be liable for damages incurred.
  4119	
  4120	         3. Distribution of information--if your site or organization
  4121	            distributes information about an attack in which another
  4122	            site or organization may be involved or the vulnerability
  4123	            in a product that may affect ability to market that
  4124	            product, your site or organization may again be liable
  4125	            for any damages (including damage of reputation).
  4126	
  4127	         4. Liabilities due to monitoring--your site or organization
  4128	            may be sued if users at your site or elsewhere discover
  4129	            that your site is monitoring account activity without
  4130	            informing users.
  4131	
  4132	      Unfortunately, there are no clear precedents yet on the
  4133	      liabilities or responsibilities of organizations involved in a
  4134	      security incident or who might be involved in supporting an
  4135	      investigative effort.  Investigators will often encourage
  4136	      organizations to help trace and monitor intruders -- indeed, most
  4137	
  4138	
  4139	
  4140	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 74]
  4141	
  4142	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  4143	
  4144	
  4145	      investigators cannot pursue computer intrusions without extensive
  4146	      support from the organizations involved.  However, investigators
  4147	      cannot provide protection from liability claims, and these kinds
  4148	      of efforts may drag out for months and may take lots of effort.
  4149	
  4150	      On the other side, an organization's legal council may advise
  4151	      extreme caution and suggest that tracing activities be halted and
  4152	      an intruder shut out of the system.  This in itself may not
  4153	      provide protection from liability, and may prevent investigators
  4154	      from identifying anyone.
  4155	
  4156	      The balance between supporting investigative activity and limiting
  4157	      liability is tricky; you'll need to consider the advice of your
  4158	      council and the damage the intruder is causing (if any) in making
  4159	      your decision about what to do during any particular incident.
  4160	
  4161	      Your legal counsel should also be involved in any decision to
  4162	      contact investigative agencies when an incident occurs at your
  4163	      site.  The decision to coordinate efforts with investigative
  4164	      agencies is most properly that of your site or organization.
  4165	      Involving your legal counsel will also foster the multi-level
  4166	      coordination between your site and the particular investigative
  4167	      agency involved which in turn results in an efficient division of
  4168	      labor.  Another result is that you are likely to obtain guidance
  4169	      that will help you avoid future legal mistakes.
  4170	
  4171	      Finally, your legal counsel should evaluate your site's written
  4172	      procedures for responding to incidents.  It is essential to obtain
  4173	      a "clean bill of health" from a legal perspective before you
  4174	      actually carry out these procedures.
  4175	
  4176	   5.5.2  Formal and Informal Legal Procedures
  4177	
  4178	      One of the most important considerations in dealing with
  4179	      investigative agencies is verifying that the person who calls
  4180	      asking for information is a legitimate representative from the
  4181	      agency in question.  Unfortunately, many well intentioned people
  4182	      have unknowingly leaked sensitive information about incidents,
  4183	      allowed unauthorized people into their systems, etc., because a
  4184	      caller has masqueraded as an FBI or Secret Service agent.  A
  4185	      similar consideration is using a secure means of communication.
  4186	      Because many network attackers can easily reroute electronic mail,
  4187	      avoid using electronic mail to communicate with other agencies (as
  4188	      well as others dealing with the incident at hand).  Non-secured
  4189	      phone lines (e.g., the phones normally used in the business world)
  4190	      are also frequent targets for tapping by network intruders, so be
  4191	      careful!
  4192	
  4193	
  4194	
  4195	
  4196	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 75]
  4197	
  4198	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  4199	
  4200	
  4201	      There is no established set of rules for responding to an incident
  4202	      when the U.S. Federal Government becomes involved.  Except by
  4203	      court order, no agency can force you to monitor, to disconnect
  4204	      from the network, to avoid telephone contact with the suspected
  4205	      attackers, etc..  As discussed in section 5.5.1, you should
  4206	      consult the matter with your legal counsel, especially before
  4207	      taking an action that your organization has never taken.  The
  4208	      particular agency involved may ask you to leave an attacked
  4209	      machine on and to monitor activity on this machine, for example.
  4210	      Your complying with this request will ensure continued cooperation
  4211	      of the agency--usually the best route towards finding the source
  4212	      of the network attacks and, ultimately, terminating these attacks.
  4213	      Additionally, you may need some information or a favor from the
  4214	      agency involved in the incident.  You are likely to get what you
  4215	      need only if you have been cooperative.  Of particular importance
  4216	      is avoiding unnecessary or unauthorized disclosure of information
  4217	      about the incident, including any information furnished by the
  4218	      agency involved.  The trust between your site and the agency
  4219	      hinges upon your ability to avoid compromising the case the agency
  4220	      will build; keeping "tight lipped" is imperative.
  4221	
  4222	      Sometimes your needs and the needs of an investigative agency will
  4223	      differ.  Your site may want to get back to normal business by
  4224	      closing an attack route, but the investigative agency may want you
  4225	      to keep this route open.  Similarly, your site may want to close a
  4226	      compromised system down to avoid the possibility of negative
  4227	      publicity, but again the investigative agency may want you to
  4228	      continue monitoring.  When there is such a conflict, there may be
  4229	      a complex set of tradeoffs (e.g., interests of your site's
  4230	      management, amount of resources you can devote to the problem,
  4231	      jurisdictional boundaries, etc.).  An important guiding principle
  4232	      is related to what might be called "Internet citizenship" [22,
  4233	      IAB89, 23] and its responsibilities.  Your site can shut a system
  4234	      down, and this will relieve you of the stress, resource demands,
  4235	      and danger of negative exposure.  The attacker, however, is likely
  4236	      to simply move on to another system, temporarily leaving others
  4237	      blind to the attacker's intention and actions until another path
  4238	      of attack can be detected.  Providing that there is no damage to
  4239	      your systems and others, the most responsible course of action is
  4240	      to cooperate with the participating agency by leaving your
  4241	      compromised system on.  This will allow monitoring (and,
  4242	      ultimately, the possibility of terminating the source of the
  4243	      threat to systems just like yours).  On the other hand, if there
  4244	      is damage to computers illegally accessed through your system, the
  4245	      choice is more complicated: shutting down the intruder may prevent
  4246	      further damage to systems, but might make it impossible to track
  4247	      down the intruder.  If there has been damage, the decision about
  4248	      whether it is important to leave systems up to catch the intruder
  4249	
  4250	
  4251	
  4252	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 76]
  4253	
  4254	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  4255	
  4256	
  4257	      should involve all the organizations effected.  Further
  4258	      complicating the issue of network responsibility is the
  4259	      consideration that if you do not cooperate with the agency
  4260	      involved, you will be less likely to receive help from that agency
  4261	      in the future.
  4262	
  4263	5.6  Documentation Logs
  4264	
  4265	   When you respond to an incident, document all details related to the
  4266	   incident.  This will provide valuable information to yourself and
  4267	   others as you try to unravel the course of events.  Documenting all
  4268	   details will ultimately save you time.  If you don't document every
  4269	   relevant phone call, for example, you are likely to forget a good
  4270	   portion of information you obtain, requiring you to contact the
  4271	   source of information once again.  This wastes yours and others'
  4272	   time, something you can ill afford.  At the same time, recording
  4273	   details will provide evidence for prosecution efforts, providing the
  4274	   case moves in this direction.  Documenting an incident also will help
  4275	   you perform a final assessment of damage (something your management
  4276	   as well as law enforcement officers will want to know), and will
  4277	   provide the basis for a follow-up analysis in which you can engage in
  4278	   a valuable "lessons learned" exercise.
  4279	
  4280	   During the initial stages of an incident, it is often infeasible to
  4281	   determine whether prosecution is viable, so you should document as if
  4282	   you are gathering evidence for a court case.  At a minimum, you
  4283	   should record:
  4284	
  4285	      o All system events (audit records).
  4286	      o All actions you take (time tagged).
  4287	      o All phone conversations (including the person with whom
  4288	        you talked, the date and time, and the content of the
  4289	        conversation).
  4290	
  4291	   The most straightforward way to maintain documentation is keeping a
  4292	   log book.  This allows you to go to a centralized, chronological
  4293	   source of information when you need it, instead of requiring you to
  4294	   page through individual sheets of paper.  Much of this information is
  4295	   potential evidence in a court of law.  Thus, when you initially
  4296	   suspect that an incident will result in prosecution or when an
  4297	   investigative agency becomes involved, you need to regularly (e.g.,
  4298	   every day) turn in photocopied, signed copies of your logbook (as
  4299	   well as media you use to record system events) to a document
  4300	   custodian who can store these copied pages in a secure place (e.g., a
  4301	   safe).  When you submit information for storage, you should in return
  4302	   receive a signed, dated receipt from the document custodian.  Failure
  4303	   to observe these procedures can result in invalidation of any
  4304	   evidence you obtain in a court of law.
  4305	
  4306	
  4307	
  4308	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 77]
  4309	
  4310	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  4311	
  4312	
  4313	6.  Establishing Post-Incident Procedures
  4314	
  4315	6.1  Overview
  4316	
  4317	   In the wake of an incident, several actions should take place.  These
  4318	   actions can be summarized as follows:
  4319	
  4320	      1. An inventory should be taken of the systems' assets,
  4321	         i.e., a careful examination should determine how the
  4322	         system was affected by the incident,
  4323	
  4324	      2. The lessons learned as a result of the incident
  4325	         should be included in revised security plan to
  4326	         prevent the incident from re-occurring,
  4327	
  4328	      3. A new risk analysis should be developed in light of the
  4329	         incident,
  4330	
  4331	      4. An investigation and prosecution of the individuals
  4332	         who caused the incident should commence, if it is
  4333	         deemed desirable.
  4334	
  4335	   All four steps should provide feedback to the site security policy
  4336	   committee, leading to prompt re-evaluation and amendment of the
  4337	   current policy.
  4338	
  4339	6.2  Removing Vulnerabilities
  4340	
  4341	   Removing all vulnerabilities once an incident has occurred is
  4342	   difficult.  The key to removing vulnerabilities is knowledge and
  4343	   understanding of the breach.  In some cases, it is prudent to remove
  4344	   all access or functionality as soon as possible, and then restore
  4345	   normal operation in limited stages.  Bear in mind that removing all
  4346	   access while an incident is in progress will obviously notify all
  4347	   users, including the alleged problem users, that the administrators
  4348	   are aware of a problem; this may have a deleterious effect on an
  4349	   investigation.  However, allowing an incident to continue may also
  4350	   open the likelihood of greater damage, loss, aggravation, or
  4351	   liability (civil or criminal).
  4352	
  4353	   If it is determined that the breach occurred due to a flaw in the
  4354	   systems' hardware or software, the vendor (or supplier) and the CERT
  4355	   should be notified as soon as possible.  Including relevant telephone
  4356	   numbers (also electronic mail addresses and fax numbers) in the site
  4357	   security policy is strongly recommended.  To aid prompt
  4358	   acknowledgment and understanding of the problem, the flaw should be
  4359	   described in as much detail as possible, including details about how
  4360	   to exploit the flaw.
  4361	
  4362	
  4363	
  4364	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 78]
  4365	
  4366	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  4367	
  4368	
  4369	   As soon as the breach has occurred, the entire system and all its
  4370	   components should be considered suspect.  System software is the most
  4371	   probable target.  Preparation is key to recovering from a possibly
  4372	   tainted system.  This includes checksumming all tapes from the vendor
  4373	   using a checksum algorithm which (hopefully) is resistant to
  4374	   tampering [10].  (See sections 3.9.4.1, 3.9.4.2.)  Assuming original
  4375	   vendor distribution tapes are available, an analysis of all system
  4376	   files should commence, and any irregularities should be noted and
  4377	   referred to all parties involved in handling the incident.  It can be
  4378	   very difficult, in some cases, to decide which backup tapes to
  4379	   recover from; consider that the incident may have continued for
  4380	   months or years before discovery, and that the suspect may be an
  4381	   employee of the site, or otherwise have intimate knowledge or access
  4382	   to the systems.  In all cases, the pre-incident preparation will
  4383	   determine what recovery is possible.  At worst-case, restoration from
  4384	   the original manufactures' media and a re-installation of the systems
  4385	   will be the most prudent solution.
  4386	
  4387	   Review the lessons learned from the incident and always update the
  4388	   policy and procedures to reflect changes necessitated by the
  4389	   incident.
  4390	
  4391	   6.2.1  Assessing Damage
  4392	
  4393	      Before cleanup can begin, the actual system damage must be
  4394	      discerned.  This can be quite time consuming, but should lead into
  4395	      some of the insight as to the nature of the incident, and aid
  4396	      investigation and prosecution.  It is best to compare previous
  4397	      backups or original tapes when possible; advance preparation is
  4398	      the key.  If the system supports centralized logging (most do), go
  4399	      back over the logs and look for abnormalities.  If process
  4400	      accounting and connect time accounting is enabled, look for
  4401	      patterns of system usage.  To a lesser extent, disk usage may shed
  4402	      light on the incident.  Accounting can provide much helpful
  4403	      information in an analysis of an incident and subsequent
  4404	      prosecution.
  4405	
  4406	   6.2.2  Cleanup
  4407	
  4408	      Once the damage has been assessed, it is necessary to develop a
  4409	      plan for system cleanup.  In general, bringing up services in the
  4410	      order of demand to allow a minimum of user inconvenience is the
  4411	      best practice.  Understand that the proper recovery procedures for
  4412	      the system are extremely important and should be specific to the
  4413	      site.
  4414	
  4415	      It may be necessary to go back to the original distributed tapes
  4416	      and recustomize the system.  To facilitate this worst case
  4417	
  4418	
  4419	
  4420	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 79]
  4421	
  4422	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  4423	
  4424	
  4425	      scenario, a record of the original systems setup and each
  4426	      customization change should be kept current with each change to
  4427	      the system.
  4428	
  4429	   6.2.3  Follow up
  4430	
  4431	      Once you believe that a system has been restored to a "safe"
  4432	      state, it is still possible that holes and even traps could be
  4433	      lurking in the system.  In the follow-up stage, the system should
  4434	      be monitored for items that may have been missed during the
  4435	      cleanup stage.  It would be prudent to utilize some of the tools
  4436	      mentioned in section 3.9.8.2 (e.g., COPS) as a start.  Remember,
  4437	      these tools don't replace continual system monitoring and good
  4438	      systems administration procedures.
  4439	
  4440	   6.2.4  Keep a Security Log
  4441	
  4442	      As discussed in section 5.6, a security log can be most valuable
  4443	      during this phase of removing vulnerabilities.  There are two
  4444	      considerations here; the first is to keep logs of the procedures
  4445	      that have been used to make the system secure again.  This should
  4446	      include command procedures (e.g., shell scripts) that can be run
  4447	      on a periodic basis to recheck the security.  Second, keep logs of
  4448	      important system events.  These can be referenced when trying to
  4449	      determine the extent of the damage of a given incident.
  4450	
  4451	6.3  Capturing Lessons Learned
  4452	
  4453	   6.3.1  Understand the Lesson
  4454	
  4455	      After an incident, it is prudent to write a report describing the
  4456	      incident, method of discovery, correction procedure, monitoring
  4457	      procedure, and a summary of lesson learned.  This will aid in the
  4458	      clear understanding of the problem.  Remember, it is difficult to
  4459	      learn from an incident if you don't understand the source.
  4460	
  4461	   6.3.2  Resources
  4462	
  4463	      6.3.2.1  Other Security Devices, Methods
  4464	
  4465	         Security is a dynamic, not static process.  Sites are dependent
  4466	         on the nature of security available at each site, and the array
  4467	         of devices and methods that will help promote security.
  4468	         Keeping up with the security area of the computer industry and
  4469	         their methods will assure a security manager of taking
  4470	         advantage of the latest technology.
  4471	
  4472	
  4473	
  4474	
  4475	
  4476	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 80]
  4477	
  4478	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  4479	
  4480	
  4481	      6.3.2.2  Repository of Books, Lists, Information Sources
  4482	
  4483	         Keep an on site collection of books, lists, information
  4484	         sources, etc., as guides and references for securing the
  4485	         system.  Keep this collection up to date.  Remember, as systems
  4486	         change, so do security methods and problems.
  4487	
  4488	      6.3.2.3  Form a Subgroup
  4489	
  4490	         Form a subgroup of system administration personnel that will be
  4491	         the core security staff.  This will allow discussions of
  4492	         security problems and multiple views of the site's security
  4493	         issues.  This subgroup can also act to develop the site
  4494	         security policy and make suggested changes as necessary to
  4495	         ensure site security.
  4496	
  4497	6.4  Upgrading Policies and Procedures
  4498	
  4499	   6.4.1  Establish Mechanisms for Updating Policies, Procedures,
  4500	          and Tools
  4501	
  4502	      If an incident is based on poor policy, and unless the policy is
  4503	      changed, then one is doomed to repeat the past.  Once a site has
  4504	      recovered from and incident, site policy and procedures should be
  4505	      reviewed to encompass changes to prevent similar incidents.  Even
  4506	      without an incident, it would be prudent to review policies and
  4507	      procedures on a regular basis.  Reviews are imperative due to
  4508	      today's changing computing environments.
  4509	
  4510	   6.4.2  Problem Reporting Procedures
  4511	
  4512	      A problem reporting procedure should be implemented to describe,
  4513	      in detail, the incident and the solutions to the incident.  Each
  4514	      incident should be reviewed by the site security subgroup to allow
  4515	      understanding of the incident with possible suggestions to the
  4516	      site policy and procedures.
  4517	
