  4750	   [BRAND]
  4751	           Brand, R., "Coping with the Threat of Computer Security
  4752	           Incidents: A Primer from Prevention through Recovery",
  4753	
  4754	
  4755	
  4756	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 85]
  4757	
  4758	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  4759	
  4760	
  4761	           R. Brand, 8 June 1990.
  4762	
  4763	           As computer security becomes a more important issue in
  4764	           modern society, it begins to warrant a systematic approach.
  4765	           The vast majority of the computer security problems and the
  4766	           costs associated with them can be prevented with simple
  4767	           inexpensive measures.  The most important and cost
  4768	           effective of these measures are available in the prevention
  4769	           and planning phases.  These methods are presented in this
  4770	           paper, followed by a simplified guide to incident
  4771	           handling and recovery.  Available on-line from:
  4772	           cert.sei.cmu.edu:/pub/info/primer.
  4773	
  4774	   [CHESWICK]
  4775	           Cheswick, B., "The Design of a Secure Internet Gateway",
  4776	           Proceedings of the Summer Usenix Conference, Anaheim, CA,
  4777	           June 1990.
  4778	
  4779	           Brief abstract (slight paraphrase from the original
  4780	           abstract): AT&T maintains a large internal Internet that
  4781	           needs to be protected from outside attacks, while
  4782	           providing useful services between the two.
  4783	           This paper describes AT&T's Internet gateway.  This
  4784	           gateway passes mail and many of the common Internet
  4785	           services between AT&T internal machines and the Internet.
  4786	           This is accomplished without IP connectivity using a pair
  4787	           of machines: a trusted internal machine and an untrusted
  4788	           external gateway.  These are connected by a private link.
  4789	           The internal machine provides a few carefully-guarded
  4790	           services to the external gateway.  This configuration
  4791	           helps protect the internal internet even if the external
  4792	           machine is fully compromised.
  4793	
  4794	           This is a very useful and interesting design.  Most
  4795	           firewall gateway systems rely on a system that, if
  4796	           compromised, could allow access to the machines behind
  4797	           the firewall.  Also, most firewall systems require users
  4798	           who want access to Internet services to have accounts on
  4799	           the firewall machine.  AT&T's design allows AT&T internal
  4800	           internet users access to the standard services of TELNET and
  4801	           FTP from their own workstations without accounts on
  4802	           the firewall machine.  A very useful paper that shows
  4803	           how to maintain some of the benefits of Internet
  4804	           connectivity while still maintaining strong
  4805	           security.
  4806	
  4807	
  4808	
  4809	
  4810	
  4811	
  4812	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 86]
  4813	
  4814	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  4815	
  4816	
  4817	   [CURRY]
  4818	           Curry, D., "Improving the Security of Your UNIX System",
  4819	           SRI International Report ITSTD-721-FR-90-21, April 1990.
  4820	
  4821	           This paper describes measures that you, as a system
  4822	           administrator can take to make your UNIX system(s) more
  4823	           secure.  Oriented primarily at SunOS 4.x, most of the
  4824	           information covered applies equally well to any Berkeley
  4825	           UNIX system with or without NFS and/or Yellow Pages (NIS).
  4826	           Some of the information can also be applied to System V,
  4827	           although this is not a primary focus of the paper.  A very
  4828	           useful reference, this is also available on the Internet in
  4829	           various locations, including the directory
  4830	           cert.sei.cmu.edu:/pub/info.
  4831	
  4832	   [FITES]
  4833	           Fites, M., Kratz, P. and A. Brebner, "Control and
  4834	           Security of Computer Information Systems", Computer Science
  4835	           Press, 1989.
  4836	
  4837	           This book serves as a good guide to the issues encountered
  4838	           in forming computer security policies and procedures.  The
  4839	           book is designed as a textbook for an introductory course
  4840	           in information systems security.
  4841	
  4842	           The book is divided into five sections: Risk Management (I),
  4843	           Safeguards: security and control measures, organizational
  4844	           and administrative (II), Safeguards: Security and Control
  4845	           Measures, Technical (III), Legal Environment and
  4846	           Professionalism (IV), and CICA Computer Control Guidelines
  4847	           (V).
  4848	
  4849	           The book is particularly notable for its straight-forward
  4850	           approach to security, emphasizing that common sense is the
  4851	           first consideration in designing a security program.  The
  4852	           authors note that there is a tendency to look to more
  4853	           technical solutions to security problems while overlooking
  4854	           organizational controls which are often cheaper and much
  4855	           more effective.  298 pages, including references and index.
  4856	
  4857	   [GARFINKEL]
  4858	           Garfinkel, S, and E. Spafford, "Practical Unix Security",
  4859	           O'Reilly & Associates, ISBN 0-937175-72-2, May 1991.
  4860	
  4861	           Approx 450 pages, $29.95.  Orders: 1-800-338-6887
  4862	           (US & Canada), 1-707-829-0515 (Europe), email: nuts@ora.com
  4863	
  4864	           This is one of the most useful books available on Unix
  4865	
  4866	
  4867	
  4868	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 87]
  4869	
  4870	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  4871	
  4872	
  4873	           security.  The first part of the book covers standard Unix
  4874	           and Unix security basics, with particular emphasis on
  4875	           passwords.  The second section covers enforcing security on
  4876	           the system.  Of particular interest to the Internet user are
  4877	           the sections on network security, which address many
  4878	           of the common security problems that afflict Internet Unix
  4879	           users.  Four chapters deal with handling security incidents,
  4880	           and the book concludes with discussions of encryption,
  4881	           physical security, and useful checklists and lists of
  4882	           resources.  The book lives up to its name; it is filled with
  4883	           specific references to possible security holes, files to
  4884	           check, and things to do to improve security.  This
  4885	           book is an excellent complement to this handbook.
  4886	
  4887	   [GREENIA90]
