  5050	8.3  Ethics
  5051	
  5052	   [CPSR89]
  5053	           Computer Professionals for Social Responsibility, "CPSR
  5054	           Statement on the Computer Virus", CPSR, Communications of the
  5055	           ACM, Vol. 32, No. 6, Pg. 699, June 1989.
  5056	
  5057	           This memo is a statement on the Internet Computer Virus
  5058	           by the Computer Professionals for Social Responsibility
  5059	           (CPSR).
  5060	
  5061	   [DENNING]
  5062	           Denning, Peter J., Editor, "Computers Under Attack:
  5063	           Intruders, Worms, and Viruses",  ACM Press, 1990.
  5064	
  5065	           A collection of 40 pieces divided into six sections: the
  5066	           emergence of worldwide computer networks, electronic breakins,
  5067	           worms, viruses, counterculture (articles examining the world
  5068	           of the "hacker"), and finally a section discussing social,
  5069	           legal, and ethical considerations.
  5070	
  5071	           A thoughtful collection that addresses the phenomenon of
  5072	           attacks on computers.  This includes a number of previously
  5073	           published articles and some new ones.  The previously
  5074	           published ones are well chosen, and include some references
  5075	           that might be otherwise hard to obtain.  This book is a key
  5076	           reference to computer security threats that have generated
  5077	           much of the concern over computer security in recent years.
  5078	
  5079	   [ERMANN]
  5080	           Ermann, D., Williams, M., and C. Gutierrez, Editors,
  5081	           "Computers, Ethics, and Society", Oxford University Press,
  5082	           NY, 1990.  (376 pages, includes bibliographical references).
  5083	
  5084	   [FORESTER]
  5085	           Forester, T., and P. Morrison, "Computer Ethics: Tales and
  5086	           Ethical Dilemmas in Computing", MIT Press, Cambridge, MA,
  5087	           1990.  (192 pages including index.)
  5088	
  5089	
  5090	
  5091	
  5092	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 91]
  5093	
  5094	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  5095	
  5096	
  5097	           From the preface: "The aim of this book is two-fold: (1) to
  5098	           describe some of the problems created by society by computers,
  5099	           and (2) to show how these problems present ethical dilemmas
  5100	           for computers professionals and computer users.
  5101	
  5102	           The problems created by computers arise, in turn, from two
  5103	           main sources: from hardware and software malfunctions and
  5104	           from misuse by human beings.  We argue that computer systems
  5105	           by their very nature are insecure, unreliable, and
  5106	           unpredictable -- and that society has yet to come to terms
  5107	           with the consequences.  We also seek to show how society
  5108	           has become newly vulnerable to human misuse of computers in
  5109	           the form of computer crime, software theft, hacking, the
  5110	           creation of viruses, invasions of privacy, and so on."
  5111	
  5112	           The eight chapters include "Computer Crime", "Software
  5113	           Theft", "Hacking and Viruses", "Unreliable Computers",
  5114	           "The Invasion of Privacy", "AI and Expert Systems",
  5115	           and "Computerizing the Workplace."  Includes extensive
  5116	           notes on sources and an index.
  5117	
