  5307	8.5  National Computer Security Center (NCSC)
  5308	
  5309	   All NCSC publications, approved for public release, are available
  5310	   from the NCSC Superintendent of Documents.
  5311	
  5312	           NCSC = National Computer Security Center
  5313	
  5314	
  5315	
  5316	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 95]
  5317	
  5318	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  5319	
  5320	
  5321	           9800 Savage Road
  5322	           Ft Meade, MD 20755-6000
  5323	
  5324	           CSC = Computer Security Center:
  5325	           an older name for the NCSC
  5326	
  5327	           NTISS = National Telecommunications and
  5328	           Information Systems Security
  5329	           NTISS Committee, National Security Agency
  5330	           Ft Meade, MD 20755-6000
  5331	
  5332	   [CSC]
  5333	           Department of Defense, "Password Management Guideline",
  5334	           CSC-STD-002-85, 12 April 1985, 31 pages.
  5335	
  5336	           The security provided by a password system depends on
  5337	           the passwords being kept secret at all times.  Thus, a
  5338	           password is vulnerable to compromise whenever it is used,
  5339	           stored, or even known.  In a password-based authentication
  5340	           mechanism implemented on an ADP system, passwords are
  5341	           vulnerable to compromise due to five essential aspects
  5342	           of the password system: 1) a password must be initially
  5343	           assigned to a user when enrolled on the ADP system;
  5344	           2) a user's password must be changed periodically;
  5345	           3) the ADP system must maintain a 'password
  5346	           database'; 4) users must remember their passwords; and
  5347	           5) users must enter their passwords into the ADP system at
  5348	           authentication time.  This guideline prescribes steps to be
  5349	           taken to minimize the vulnerability of passwords in each of
  5350	           these circumstances.
  5351	
  5352	   [NCSC1]
  5353	           NCSC, "A Guide to Understanding AUDIT in Trusted Systems",
  5354	           NCSC-TG-001, Version-2, 1 June 1988, 25 pages.
  5355	
  5356	           Audit trails are used to detect and deter penetration of
  5357	           a computer system and to reveal usage that identifies
  5358	           misuse.  At the discretion of the auditor, audit trails
  5359	           may be limited to specific events or may encompass all of
  5360	           the activities on a system.  Although not required by
  5361	           the criteria, it should be possible for the target of the
  5362	           audit mechanism to be either a subject or an object.  That
  5363	           is to say, the audit mechanism should be capable of
  5364	           monitoring every time John accessed the system as well as
  5365	           every time the nuclear reactor file was accessed; and
  5366	           likewise every time John accessed the nuclear reactor
  5367	           file.
  5368	
  5369	
  5370	
  5371	
  5372	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 96]
  5373	
  5374	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  5375	
  5376	
  5377	   [NCSC2]
  5378	           NCSC, "A Guide to Understanding DISCRETIONARY ACCESS CONTROL
  5379	           in Trusted Systems", NCSC-TG-003, Version-1, 30 September
  5380	           1987, 29 pages.
  5381	
  5382	           Discretionary control is the most common type of access
  5383	           control mechanism implemented in computer systems today.
  5384	           The basis of this kind of security is that an individual
  5385	           user, or program operating on the user's behalf, is
  5386	           allowed to specify explicitly the types of access other
  5387	           users (or programs executing on their behalf) may have to
  5388	           information under the user's control.  [...]  Discretionary
  5389	           controls are not a replacement for mandatory controls.  In
  5390	           any environment in which information is protected,
  5391	           discretionary security provides for a finer granularity of
  5392	           control within the overall constraints of the mandatory
  5393	           policy.
  5394	
  5395	   [NCSC3]
  5396	           NCSC, "A Guide to Understanding CONFIGURATION MANAGEMENT
  5397	           in Trusted Systems", NCSC-TG-006, Version-1, 28 March 1988,
  5398	           31 pages.
  5399	
  5400	           Configuration management consists of four separate tasks:
  5401	           identification, control, status accounting, and auditing.
  5402	           For every change that is made to an automated data
  5403	           processing (ADP) system, the design and requirements of the
  5404	           changed version of the system should be identified.  The
  5405	           control task of configuration management is performed
  5406	           by subjecting every change to documentation, hardware, and
  5407	           software/firmware to review and approval by an authorized
  5408	           authority.  Configuration status accounting is responsible
  5409	           for recording and reporting on the configuration of the
  5410	           product throughout the change.  Finally, though the process
  5411	           of a configuration audit, the completed change can be
  5412	           verified to be functionally correct, and for trusted
  5413	           systems, consistent with the security policy of the system.
  5414	
  5415	   [NTISS]
  5416	           NTISS, "Advisory Memorandum on Office Automation Security
  5417	           Guideline", NTISSAM CONPUSEC/1-87, 16 January 1987,
  5418	           58 pages.
  5419	
  5420	           This document provides guidance to users, managers, security
  5421	           officers, and procurement officers of Office Automation
  5422	           Systems.  Areas addressed include: physical security,
  5423	           personnel security, procedural security, hardware/software
  5424	           security, emanations security (TEMPEST), and communications
  5425	
  5426	
  5427	
  5428	Site Security Policy Handbook Working Group                    [Page 97]
  5429	
  5430	RFC 1244                 Site Security Handbook                July 1991
  5431	
  5432	
  5433	           security for stand-alone OA Systems, OA Systems
  5434	           used as terminals connected to mainframe computer systems,
  5435	           and OA Systems used as hosts in a Local Area Network (LAN).
  5436	           Differentiation is made between those Office Automation
  5437	           Systems equipped with removable storage media only (e.g.,
  5438	           floppy disks, cassette tapes, removable hard disks) and
  5439	           those Office Automation Systems equipped with fixed media
  5440	           (e.g., Winchester disks).
